1
00:00:00,079 --> 00:00:00,760
THE VIRGINIAN

2
00:00:00,760 --> 00:00:03,800
by Owen WISTER

3
00:00:03,800 --> 00:00:05,122
CHAPTER I

4
00:00:05,122 --> 00:00:05,883
Enter the Man

5
00:00:05,883 --> 00:00:10,730
Some notable sight was drawing the
passengers, both men and women,

6
00:00:10,730 --> 00:00:15,896
to the window; and therefore I rose and
crossed the car to see what it was.

7
00:00:15,896 --> 00:00:20,309
I saw near the track an enclosure,
and round it some laughing men,

8
00:00:20,309 --> 00:00:24,719
and inside it some whirling dust,
and amid the dust some horses,

9
00:00:24,719 --> 00:00:27,150
plunging, huddling, and dodging.

10
00:00:27,150 --> 00:00:31,944
They were cow ponies in a corral,
and one of them would not be caught,

11
00:00:31,944 --> 00:00:33,296
no matter who threw the rope.

12
00:00:33,296 --> 00:00:37,359
We had plenty of time to watch this
sport, for our train had stopped that

13
00:00:37,359 --> 00:00:41,436
the engine might take water at the tank
before it pulled us up beside the

14
00:00:41,436 --> 00:00:43,596
station platform of Medicine Bow.

15
00:00:43,596 --> 00:00:48,268
We were also six hours late,
and starving for entertainment.

16
00:00:48,268 --> 00:00:52,436
The pony in the corral was wise,
and rapid of limb.

17
00:00:52,436 --> 00:00:59,323
Have you seen a skilful boxer watch his
antagonist with a quiet, incessant eye?

18
00:00:59,323 --> 00:01:04,563
Such an eye as this did the pony keep
upon whatever man took the rope.

19
00:01:04,563 --> 00:01:07,561
The man might pretend to look at the
weather, which was fine;

20
00:01:07,561 --> 00:01:12,284
or he might affect earnest conversation
with a bystander: it was bootless.

21
00:01:12,284 --> 00:01:13,955
The pony saw through it.

22
00:01:13,955 --> 00:01:16,426
No feint hoodwinked him.

23
00:01:16,426 --> 00:01:19,811
This animal was thoroughly a
man of the world.

24
00:01:19,811 --> 00:01:23,750
His undistracted eye stayed fixed upon
the dissembling foe,

25
00:01:23,750 --> 00:01:27,555
and the gravity of his horse-expression
made the matter one of high comedy.

26
00:01:27,555 --> 00:01:30,989
Then the rope would sail out at him,
but he was already elsewhere;

27
00:01:30,989 --> 00:01:34,682
and if horses laugh,
gaiety must have abounded in that

28
00:01:34,682 --> 00:01:35,373
corral.

29
00:01:35,373 --> 00:01:39,714
Sometimes the pony took a turn alone;
next he had slid in a flash among his

30
00:01:39,714 --> 00:01:43,783
brothers, and the whole of them like a
school of playful fish whipped round the

31
00:01:43,783 --> 00:01:50,207
corral, kicking up the fine dust,
and (I take it) roaring with laughter.

32
00:01:50,207 --> 00:01:54,548
Through the window-glass of our Pullman
the thud of their mischievous hoofs

33
00:01:54,548 --> 00:01:59,819
reached us, and the strong,
humorous curses of the cowboys.

34
00:01:59,819 --> 00:02:04,100
Then for the first time I noticed a man
who sat on the high gate of

35
00:02:04,100 --> 00:02:05,989
the corral, looking on.

36
00:02:05,989 --> 00:02:09,203
For he now climbed down with the
undulations of a tiger,

37
00:02:09,203 --> 00:02:13,539
smooth and easy, as if his muscles
flowed beneath his skin.

38
00:02:13,539 --> 00:02:19,807
The others had all visibly whirled the
rope, some of them even shoulder high.

39
00:02:19,807 --> 00:02:23,640
I did not see his arm lift or move.

40
00:02:23,640 --> 00:02:26,851
He appeared to hold the rope down
low, by his leg.

41
00:02:26,851 --> 00:02:31,800
But like a sudden snake I saw the noose
go out its length and fall true;

42
00:02:31,800 --> 00:02:33,172
and the thing was done.

43
00:02:33,172 --> 00:02:38,052
As the captured pony walked in with a
sweet, church-door expression,

44
00:02:38,052 --> 00:02:42,895
our train moved slowly on to the
station, and a passenger remarked,

45
00:02:42,895 --> 00:02:45,936
“That man knows his business.”

46
00:02:45,936 --> 00:02:51,268
But the passenger’s dissertation upon
roping I was obliged to lose,

47
00:02:51,268 --> 00:02:54,349
for Medicine Bow was my station.

48
00:02:54,349 --> 00:02:59,523
I bade my fellow-travellers goodbye,
and descended, a stranger,

49
00:02:59,523 --> 00:03:01,440
into the great cattle land.

50
00:03:01,440 --> 00:03:05,020
And here in less than ten minutes I
learned news which made me

51
00:03:05,020 --> 00:03:07,930
feel a stranger indeed.

52
00:03:07,930 --> 00:03:13,053
My baggage was lost; it had not come on
my train; it was adrift somewhere back

53
00:03:13,053 --> 00:03:15,435
in the two thousand miles
that lay behind me.

54
00:03:15,435 --> 00:03:20,669
And by way of comfort,
the baggage-man remarked that passengers

55
00:03:20,669 --> 00:03:25,710
often got astray from their trunks,
but the trunks mostly found

56
00:03:25,710 --> 00:03:26,697
them after a while.

57
00:03:26,697 --> 00:03:30,538
Having offered me this encouragement,
he turned whistling to his affairs and

58
00:03:30,538 --> 00:03:33,528
left me planted in the baggage-
room at Medicine Bow.

59
00:03:33,528 --> 00:03:39,443
I stood deserted among crates and boxes,
blankly holding my check,

60
00:03:39,443 --> 00:03:41,541
hungry and forlorn.

61
00:03:41,541 --> 00:03:45,682
I stared out through the door at the sky
and the plains; but I did not see the

62
00:03:45,682 --> 00:03:50,401
antelope shining among the sagebrush,
nor the great sunset light of Wyoming.

63
00:03:50,401 --> 00:03:56,308
Annoyance blinded my eyes to all things
save my grievance: I saw

64
00:03:56,308 --> 00:03:57,708
only a lost trunk.

65
00:03:57,708 --> 00:04:01,195
And I was muttering half-aloud,
“What a forsaken hole this is!”

66
00:04:01,195 --> 00:04:05,291
when suddenly from outside on the
platform came a slow voice:⁠—

67
00:04:05,291 --> 00:04:06,809
“Off to get married again?

68
00:04:06,809 --> 00:04:07,964
Oh, don’t!”

69
00:04:07,964 --> 00:04:13,641
The voice was Southern and gentle and
drawling; and a second voice came in

70
00:04:13,641 --> 00:04:15,522
immediate answer, cracked
and querulous:⁠—

71
00:04:15,522 --> 00:04:16,728
“It ain’t again.

72
00:04:16,728 --> 00:04:18,166
Who says it’s again?

73
00:04:18,166 --> 00:04:19,446
Who told you, anyway?”

74
00:04:19,446 --> 00:04:22,575
And the first voice responded
caressingly:⁠—

75
00:04:22,575 --> 00:04:25,004
“Why, your Sunday clothes
told me, Uncle Hughey.

76
00:04:25,004 --> 00:04:28,153
They are speakin’ mighty
loud o’ nuptials.”

77
00:04:28,153 --> 00:04:30,176
“You don’t worry me!”

78
00:04:30,176 --> 00:04:32,342
snapped Uncle Hughey, with shrill heat.

79
00:04:32,342 --> 00:04:36,938
And the other gently continued,
“Ain’t them gloves the same yu’ wore

80
00:04:36,938 --> 00:04:38,376
to your last weddin’?”

81
00:04:38,376 --> 00:04:39,776
“You don’t worry me!

82
00:04:39,776 --> 00:04:41,394
You don’t worry me!”

83
00:04:41,394 --> 00:04:43,336
now screamed Uncle Hughey.

84
00:04:43,336 --> 00:04:47,867
Already I had forgotten my trunk;
care had left me; I was aware of the

85
00:04:47,867 --> 00:04:52,277
sunset, and had no desire but for
more of this conversation.

86
00:04:52,277 --> 00:04:55,756
For it resembled none that I had heard in
my life so far.

87
00:04:55,756 --> 00:04:59,157
I stepped to the door and looked out
upon the station platform.

88
00:04:59,157 --> 00:05:04,238
Lounging there at ease against the wall
was a slim young giant,

89
00:05:04,238 --> 00:05:06,084
more beautiful than pictures.

90
00:05:06,084 --> 00:05:11,862
His broad, soft hat was pushed back;
a loose-knotted, dull-scarlet

91
00:05:11,862 --> 00:05:16,344
handkerchief sagged from his throat;
and one casual thumb was hooked in the

92
00:05:16,344 --> 00:05:19,893
cartridge-belt that slanted
across his hips.

93
00:05:19,893 --> 00:05:25,477
He had plainly come many miles from
somewhere across the vast horizon,

94
00:05:25,477 --> 00:05:28,289
as the dust upon him showed.

95
00:05:28,289 --> 00:05:30,138
His boots were white with it.

96
00:05:30,138 --> 00:05:31,748
His overalls were gray with it.

97
00:05:31,748 --> 00:05:35,147
The weather-beaten bloom of his face
shone through it duskily,

98
00:05:35,147 --> 00:05:39,255
as the ripe peaches look upon their
trees in a dry season.

99
00:05:39,255 --> 00:05:44,109
But no dinginess of travel or shabbiness
of attire could tarnish the splendor

100
00:05:44,109 --> 00:05:46,580
that radiated from his
youth and strength.

101
00:05:46,580 --> 00:05:52,922
The old man upon whose temper his remarks
were doing such deadly work was combed

102
00:05:52,922 --> 00:05:57,343
and curried to a finish,
a bridegroom swept and garnished;

103
00:05:57,343 --> 00:05:59,489
but alas for age!

104
00:05:59,489 --> 00:06:02,056
Had I been the bride,
I should have taken the

105
00:06:02,056 --> 00:06:04,693
giant, dust and all.

106
00:06:04,693 --> 00:06:08,114
He had by no means done with the old man.

107
00:06:08,114 --> 00:06:11,557
“Why, yu’ve hung weddin’
gyarments on every limb!”

108
00:06:11,557 --> 00:06:14,480
he now drawled, with admiration.

109
00:06:14,480 --> 00:06:16,492
“Who is the lucky lady this trip?”

110
00:06:16,492 --> 00:06:18,760
The old man seemed to vibrate.

111
00:06:18,760 --> 00:06:20,210
“Tell you there ain’t been no other!

112
00:06:20,210 --> -1:59:59,000
Call me a Mormon, would you?

113
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

114
00:06:22,800 --> 00:06:25,338
“Why, that⁠—”

115
00:06:25,338 --> 00:06:26,583
“Call me a Mormon?

116
00:06:26,583 --> 00:06:28,782
Then name some of my wives.

117
00:06:28,782 --> 00:06:30,641
Name two.

118
00:06:30,641 --> 00:06:32,515
Name one.

119
00:06:32,515 --> 00:06:33,307
Dare you!”

120
00:06:33,307 --> 00:06:35,232
“⁠—that Laramie wido’ promised you⁠—”

121
00:06:35,232 --> 00:06:36,185
“Shucks!”

122
00:06:36,185 --> 00:06:40,988
“⁠—only her doctor suddenly
ordered Southern climate and⁠—”

123
00:06:40,988 --> 00:06:42,239
“Shucks!

124
00:06:42,239 --> 00:06:43,429
You’re a false alarm.”

125
00:06:43,429 --> 00:06:46,539
“⁠—so nothing but her
lungs came between you.

126
00:06:46,539 --> 00:06:50,597
And next you’d most got united
with Cattle Kate, only⁠—”

127
00:06:50,597 --> 00:06:52,459
“Tell you you’re a false alarm!”

128
00:06:52,459 --> -1:59:59,000
“⁠—only she got hung.

129
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

130
00:06:54,262 --> 00:06:55,947
“Where’s the wives in all this?

131
00:06:55,947 --> 00:06:58,598
Show the wives!

132
00:06:58,598 --> 00:06:59,452
Come now!”

133
00:06:59,452 --> 00:07:03,333
“That corn-fed biscuit-shooter at Rawlins
yu’ gave the canary⁠—”

134
00:07:03,333 --> 00:07:04,319
“Never married her.

135
00:07:04,319 --> 00:07:05,369
Never did marry⁠—”

136
00:07:05,369 --> 00:07:07,111
“But yu’ come so near, uncle!

137
00:07:07,111 --> 00:07:10,384
She was the one left yu’ that letter
explaining how she’d got married to a

138
00:07:10,384 --> 00:07:14,625
young cyard-player the very day before
her ceremony with you was due, and⁠—”

139
00:07:14,625 --> 00:07:18,855
“Oh, you’re nothing; you’re a kid;
you don’t amount to⁠—”

140
00:07:18,855 --> 00:07:23,295
“⁠—and how she’d never,
never forgot to feed the canary.”

141
00:07:23,295 --> 00:07:28,006
“This country’s getting full of kids,”
stated the old man, witheringly.

142
00:07:28,006 --> 00:07:29,173
“It’s doomed.”

143
00:07:29,173 --> 00:07:32,244
This crushing assertion
plainly satisfied him.

144
00:07:32,244 --> 00:07:35,953
And he blinked his eyes
with renewed anticipation.

145
00:07:35,953 --> 00:07:39,884
His tall tormentor continued with a face
of unchanging gravity,

146
00:07:39,884 --> 00:07:43,589
and a voice of gentle solicitude:⁠—

147
00:07:43,589 --> 00:07:45,282
“How is the health of that unfortunate⁠—”

148
00:07:45,282 --> 00:07:46,215
“That’s right!

149
00:07:46,215 --> 00:07:47,809
Pour your insults!

150
00:07:47,809 --> 00:07:50,973
Pour ’em on a sick, afflicted woman!”

151
00:07:50,973 --> 00:07:53,892
The eyes blinked with combative relish.

152
00:07:53,892 --> 00:07:55,582
“Insults?

153
00:07:55,582 --> 00:07:58,180
Oh, no, Uncle Hughey!”

154
00:07:58,180 --> 00:07:59,260
“That’s all right!

155
00:07:59,260 --> 00:08:00,786
Insults goes!”

156
00:08:00,786 --> 00:08:06,848
“Why, I was mighty relieved when she
began to recover her mem’ry.

157
00:08:06,848 --> 00:08:11,290
Las’ time I heard, they told me she’d got
it pretty near all back.

158
00:08:11,290 --> 00:08:15,014
Remembered her father,
and her mother, and her sisters and

159
00:08:15,014 --> 00:08:18,771
brothers, and her friends,
and her happy childhood,

160
00:08:18,771 --> 00:08:21,677
and all her doin’s except only your
face.

161
00:08:21,677 --> 00:08:24,940
The boys was bettin’ she’d get that far
too, give her time.

162
00:08:24,940 --> 00:08:28,377
But I reckon afteh such a turrable
sickness as she had,

163
00:08:28,377 --> 00:08:31,461
that would be expectin’ most too much.”

164
00:08:31,461 --> 00:08:34,601
At this Uncle Hughey jerked
out a small parcel.

165
00:08:34,601 --> 00:08:36,600
“Shows how much you know!”

166
00:08:36,600 --> 00:08:37,382
he cackled.

167
00:08:37,382 --> 00:08:38,258
“There!

168
00:08:38,258 --> 00:08:39,372
See that!

169
00:08:39,372 --> 00:08:44,914
That’s my ring she sent me back,
being too unstrung for marriage.

170
00:08:44,914 --> 00:08:47,794
So she don’t remember me, don’t she?

171
00:08:47,794 --> 00:08:48,306
Ha-ha!

172
00:08:48,306 --> 00:08:50,866
Always said you were a false alarm.”

173
00:08:50,866 --> 00:08:53,490
The Southerner put more
anxiety into his tone.

174
00:08:53,490 --> 00:08:56,382
“And so you’re a-takin’ the ring right on
to the next one!”

175
00:08:56,382 --> 00:08:57,727
he exclaimed.

176
00:08:57,727 --> 00:09:01,115
“Oh, don’t go to get married
again, Uncle Hughey!

177
00:09:01,115 --> 00:09:03,844
What’s the use o’ being married?”

178
00:09:03,844 --> 00:09:05,737
“What’s the use?”

179
00:09:05,737 --> 00:09:08,109
echoed the bridegroom, with scorn.

180
00:09:08,109 --> 00:09:09,209
“Hm!

181
00:09:09,209 --> 00:09:11,553
When you grow up you’ll think different.”

182
00:09:11,553 --> 00:09:15,972
“Course I expect to think different when
my age is different.

183
00:09:15,972 --> 00:09:18,841
I’m havin’ the thoughts proper to twenty-
four, and you’re havin’ the

184
00:09:18,841 --> -1:59:59,000
thoughts proper to sixty.

185
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

186
00:09:20,552 --> 00:09:21,058
“Fifty!”

187
00:09:21,058 --> 00:09:23,933
shrieked Uncle Hughey, jumping in the air.

188
00:09:23,933 --> 00:09:27,346
The Southerner took a
tone of self-reproach.

189
00:09:27,346 --> 00:09:33,189
“Now, how could I forget you was fifty,”
he murmured, “when you have been telling

190
00:09:33,189 --> 00:09:36,225
it to the boys so careful for
the last ten years!”

191
00:09:36,225 --> 00:09:42,204
Have you ever seen a cockatoo⁠—the white
kind with the topknot⁠—enraged by

192
00:09:42,204 --> 00:09:43,045
insult?

193
00:09:43,045 --> 00:09:48,384
The bird erects every available
feather upon its person.

194
00:09:48,384 --> 00:09:53,573
So did Uncle Hughey seem to swell,
clothes, mustache, and woolly white

195
00:09:53,573 --> 00:09:57,799
beard; and without further speech he
took himself on board the Eastbound

196
00:09:57,799 --> 00:10:01,659
train, which now arrived from its siding
in time to deliver him.

197
00:10:01,659 --> 00:10:05,901
Yet this was not why he had
not gone away before.

198
00:10:05,901 --> 00:10:10,221
At any time he could have escaped into
the baggage-room or withdrawn to a

199
00:10:10,221 --> 00:10:13,689
dignified distance until his
train should come up.

200
00:10:13,689 --> 00:10:17,853
But the old man had evidently got a sort
of joy from this teasing.

201
00:10:17,853 --> 00:10:21,641
He had reached that inevitable age when
we are tickled to be linked with affairs

202
00:10:21,641 --> 00:10:23,695
of gallantry, no matter how.

203
00:10:23,695 --> 00:10:28,391
With him now the Eastbound departed
slowly into that distance

204
00:10:28,391 --> 00:10:29,471
whence I had come.

205
00:10:29,471 --> 00:10:34,425
I stared after it as it went its way to
the far shores of civilization.

206
00:10:34,425 --> 00:10:39,818
It grew small in the unending gulf of
space, until all sign of its presence

207
00:10:39,818 --> 00:10:44,810
was gone save a faint skein of smoke
against the evening sky.

208
00:10:44,810 --> 00:10:50,717
And now my lost trunk came back into my
thoughts, and Medicine Bow

209
00:10:50,717 --> 00:10:52,573
seemed a lonely spot.

210
00:10:52,573 --> 00:10:56,695
A sort of ship had left me marooned in a
foreign ocean; the Pullman was

211
00:10:56,695 --> 00:11:00,283
comfortably steaming home to port,
while I⁠—how was I to

212
00:11:00,283 --> 00:11:02,203
find Judge Henry’s ranch?

213
00:11:02,203 --> 00:11:07,899
Where in this unfeatured
wilderness was Sunk Creek?

214
00:11:07,899 --> 00:11:11,908
No creek or any water at all flowed here
that I could perceive.

215
00:11:11,908 --> 00:11:17,099
My host had written he should meet me at
the station and drive me to his ranch.

216
00:11:17,099 --> 00:11:18,847
This was all that I knew.

217
00:11:18,847 --> 00:11:20,291
He was not here.

218
00:11:20,291 --> 00:11:22,952
The baggage-man had not seen him lately.

219
00:11:22,952 --> 00:11:27,229
The ranch was almost certain to be too
far to walk to, tonight.

220
00:11:27,229 --> 00:11:32,479
My trunk⁠—I discovered myself still
staring dolefully after the vanished

221
00:11:32,479 --> 00:11:37,784
Eastbound; and at the same instant I
became aware that the tall man was

222
00:11:37,784 --> 00:11:42,546
looking gravely at me⁠—as gravely as he
had looked at Uncle Hughey

223
00:11:42,546 --> 00:11:46,186
throughout their remarkable
conversation.

224
00:11:46,186 --> 00:11:51,157
To see his eye thus fixing me and his
thumb still hooked in his cartridge-

225
00:11:51,157 --> 00:11:55,478
belt, certain tales of travellers from
these parts forced themselves

226
00:11:55,478 --> 00:11:57,641
disquietingly into my recollection.

227
00:11:57,641 --> 00:12:02,298
Now that Uncle Hughey was gone,
was I to take his place and be,

228
00:12:02,298 --> 00:12:07,074
for instance, invited to dance on the
platform to the music

229
00:12:07,074 --> 00:12:08,755
of shots nicely aimed?

230
00:12:08,755 --> 00:12:12,332
“I reckon I am looking for you,
seh,” the tall man now observed.

231
00:12:12,332 --> 00:12:13,274
CHAPTER II

232
00:12:13,274 --> 00:12:15,182
“When You Call Me That,Smile!”

233
00:12:15,182 --> 00:12:20,226
We cannot see ourselves as others see us,
or I should know what appearance I cut

234
00:12:20,226 --> 00:12:21,992
at hearing this from the tall man.

235
00:12:21,992 --> 00:12:24,252
I said nothing, feeling uncertain.

236
00:12:24,252 --> 00:12:27,831
“I reckon I am looking for you,
seh,” he repeated politely.

237
00:12:27,831 --> 00:12:31,727
“I am looking for Judge
Henry,” I now replied.

238
00:12:31,727 --> 00:12:36,220
He walked toward me, and I saw that in
inches he was not a giant.

239
00:12:36,220 --> 00:12:39,060
He was not more than six feet.

240
00:12:39,060 --> 00:12:42,665
It was Uncle Hughey that had made
him seem to tower.

241
00:12:42,665 --> 00:12:47,509
But in his eye, in his face,
in his step, in the whole man,

242
00:12:47,509 --> 00:12:53,244
there dominated a something potent to be
felt, I should think, by man or woman.

243
00:12:53,244 --> 00:12:56,465
“The Judge sent me afteh you,
seh,” he now explained,

244
00:12:56,465 --> 00:13:00,436
in his civil Southern voice;
and he handed me a letter from my host.

245
00:13:00,436 --> 00:13:03,859
Had I not witnessed his facetious
performances with Uncle Hughey,

246
00:13:03,859 --> 00:13:07,516
I should have judged him wholly
ungifted with such powers.

247
00:13:07,516 --> 00:13:11,747
There was nothing external about him but
what seemed the signs of a nature as

248
00:13:11,747 --> 00:13:13,370
grave as you could meet.

249
00:13:13,370 --> 00:13:17,878
But I had witnessed; and therefore
supposing that I knew him in spite of

250
00:13:17,878 --> 00:13:22,149
his appearance, that I was,
so to speak, in his secret and could

251
00:13:22,149 --> 00:13:26,564
give him a sort of wink,
I adopted at once a method of easiness.

252
00:13:26,564 --> 00:13:31,721
It was so pleasant to be easy with a
large stranger, who instead of shooting

253
00:13:31,721 --> 00:13:36,586
at your heels had very civilly
handed you a letter.

254
00:13:36,586 --> 00:13:38,843
“You’re from old Virginia, I take it?”

255
00:13:38,843 --> 00:13:40,092
I began.

256
00:13:40,092 --> 00:13:45,487
He answered slowly, “Then you have
taken it correct, seh.”

257
00:13:45,487 --> 00:13:50,831
A slight chill passed over my easiness,
but I went cheerily on

258
00:13:50,831 --> 00:13:52,551
with a further inquiry.

259
00:13:52,551 --> 00:13:55,594
“Find many oddities out
here like Uncle Hughey?”

260
00:13:55,594 --> 00:14:00,014
“Yes, seh, there is a right
smart of oddities around.

261
00:14:00,014 --> 00:14:01,700
They come in on every train.”

262
00:14:01,700 --> 00:14:04,715
At this point I dropped
my method of easiness.

263
00:14:04,715 --> 00:14:08,115
“I wish that trunks came on
the train,” said I.

264
00:14:08,115 --> 00:14:11,609
And I told him my predicament.

265
00:14:11,609 --> 00:14:15,367
It was not to be expected that he would
be greatly moved at my loss;

266
00:14:15,367 --> 00:14:17,678
but he took it with no comment whatever.

267
00:14:17,678 --> 00:14:21,948
“We’ll wait in town for it,”
said he, always perfectly civil.

268
00:14:21,948 --> 00:14:27,040
Now, what I had seen of “town” was,
to my newly arrived eyes,

269
00:14:27,040 --> 00:14:28,811
altogether horrible.

270
00:14:28,811 --> 00:14:33,191
If I could possibly sleep at the Judge’s
ranch, I preferred to do so.

271
00:14:33,191 --> 00:14:35,044
“Is it too far to drive there tonight?”

272
00:14:35,044 --> 00:14:35,982
I inquired.

273
00:14:35,982 --> 00:14:38,214
He looked at me in a puzzled manner.

274
00:14:38,214 --> 00:14:43,516
“For this valise,” I explained,
“contains all that I immediately need;

275
00:14:43,516 --> 00:14:47,313
in fact, I could do without my trunk for
a day or two, if it is

276
00:14:47,313 --> 00:14:48,773
not convenient to send.

277
00:14:48,773 --> 00:14:54,172
So if we could arrive there not too late
by starting at once⁠—” I paused.

278
00:14:54,172 --> 00:14:58,020
“It’s two hundred and sixty-three
miles,” said the Virginian.

279
00:14:58,020 --> 00:15:02,583
To my loud ejaculation he made no answer,
but surveyed me a moment longer,

280
00:15:02,583 --> 00:15:05,676
and then said, “Supper will
be about ready now.”

281
00:15:05,676 --> 00:15:09,755
He took my valise, and I followed his
steps toward the eating-house in

282
00:15:09,755 --> 00:15:10,746
silence.

283
00:15:10,746 --> 00:15:12,137
I was dazed.

284
00:15:12,137 --> 00:15:17,690
As we went, I read my host’s letter⁠—
a brief hospitable message.

285
00:15:17,690 --> 00:15:21,517
He was very sorry not to meet me himself.

286
00:15:21,517 --> 00:15:25,756
He had been getting ready to drive over,
when the surveyor appeared

287
00:15:25,756 --> 00:15:26,554
and detained him.

288
00:15:26,554 --> 00:15:30,595
Therefore in his stead he was sending a
trustworthy man to town,

289
00:15:30,595 --> 00:15:33,735
who would look after me
and drive me over.

290
00:15:33,735 --> 00:15:37,812
They were looking forward to my
visit with much pleasure.

291
00:15:37,812 --> 00:15:39,038
This was all.

292
00:15:39,038 --> 00:15:41,285
Yes, I was dazed.

293
00:15:41,285 --> 00:15:43,827
How did they count distance
in this country?

294
00:15:43,827 --> 00:15:48,974
You spoke in a neighborly fashion about
driving over to town,

295
00:15:48,974 --> 00:15:52,724
and it meant⁠—I did not know
yet how many days.

296
00:15:52,724 --> 00:15:56,750
And what would be meant by the term
“dropping in,” I wondered.

297
00:15:56,750 --> 00:16:01,033
And how many miles would
be considered really far?

298
00:16:01,033 --> 00:16:05,311
I abstained from further
questioning the “trustworthy man.”

299
00:16:05,311 --> 00:16:07,798
My questions had not fared
excessively well.

300
00:16:07,798 --> 00:16:11,338
He did not propose making me dance,
to be sure: that would

301
00:16:11,338 --> 00:16:13,098
scarcely be trustworthy.

302
00:16:13,098 --> 00:16:16,066
But neither did he propose to have
me familiar with him.

303
00:16:16,066 --> 00:16:17,359
Why was this?

304
00:16:17,359 --> 00:16:24,112
What had I done to elicit that veiled and
skilful sarcasm about oddities coming

305
00:16:24,112 --> 00:16:25,361
in on every train?

306
00:16:25,361 --> 00:16:29,512
Having been sent to look after me,
he would do so, would even carry my

307
00:16:29,512 --> 00:16:32,792
valise; but I could not
be jocular with him.

308
00:16:32,792 --> 00:16:38,215
This handsome, ungrammatical son of the
soil had set between us the bar of his

309
00:16:38,215 --> 00:16:40,211
cold and perfect civility.

310
00:16:40,211 --> 00:16:42,810
No polished person could
have done it better.

311
00:16:42,810 --> 00:16:43,980
What was the matter?

312
00:16:43,980 --> 00:16:46,473
I looked at him, and suddenly
it came to me.

313
00:16:46,473 --> 00:16:51,001
If he had tried familiarity with me the
first two minutes of our acquaintance,

314
00:16:51,001 --> 00:16:54,086
I should have resented it;
by what right, then,

315
00:16:54,086 --> 00:16:55,339
had I tried it with him?

316
00:16:55,339 --> 00:17:00,051
It smacked of patronizing:
on this occasion he had come off the

317
00:17:00,051 --> 00:17:01,724
better gentleman of the two.

318
00:17:01,724 --> 00:17:06,775
Here in flesh and blood was a truth which
I had long believed in words,

319
00:17:06,775 --> 00:17:08,542
but never met before.

320
00:17:08,542 --> 00:17:14,186
The creature we call a gentleman lies
deep in the hearts of thousands that are

321
00:17:14,186 --> 00:17:18,338
born without chance to master the
outward graces of the type.

322
00:17:18,338 --> 00:17:21,656
Between the station and the eating-house
I did a deal of straight thinking.

323
00:17:21,656 --> 00:17:26,178
But my thoughts were destined presently
to be drowned in amazement at the rare

324
00:17:26,178 --> 00:17:29,486
personage into whose society
fate had thrown me.

325
00:17:29,486 --> 00:17:33,678
Town, as they called it,
pleased me the less, the longer I saw

326
00:17:33,678 --> 00:17:33,987
it.

327
00:17:33,987 --> 00:17:38,958
But until our language stretches itself
and takes in a new word of closer fit,

328
00:17:38,958 --> 00:17:43,518
town will have to do for the name of
such a place as was Medicine Bow.

329
00:17:43,518 --> 00:17:48,213
I have seen and slept in
many like it since.

330
00:17:48,213 --> 00:17:52,062
Scattered wide, they littered the
frontier from the Columbia to the Rio

331
00:17:52,062 --> 00:17:55,301
Grande, from the Missouri to the
Sierras.

332
00:17:55,301 --> 00:18:00,059
They lay stark, dotted over a planet of
treeless dust, like soiled

333
00:18:00,059 --> 00:18:01,386
packs of cards.

334
00:18:01,386 --> 00:18:05,233
Each was similar to the next,
as one old five-spot

335
00:18:05,233 --> 00:18:07,139
of clubs resembles another.

336
00:18:07,139 --> 00:18:11,133
Houses, empty bottles,
and garbage, they were forever of

337
00:18:11,133 --> 00:18:13,774
the same shapeless pattern.

338
00:18:13,774 --> 00:18:17,264
More forlorn they were than stale bones.

339
00:18:17,264 --> 00:18:22,299
They seemed to have been strewn there by
the wind and to be waiting till the wind

340
00:18:22,299 --> 00:18:24,671
should come again and blow them away.

341
00:18:24,671 --> 00:18:29,212
Yet serene above their foulness swam a
pure and quiet light,

342
00:18:29,212 --> 00:18:33,672
such as the East never sees;
they might be bathing in the air

343
00:18:33,672 --> 00:18:36,783
of creation’s first morning.

344
00:18:36,783 --> 00:18:43,036
Beneath sun and stars their days and
nights were immaculate and wonderful.

345
00:18:43,036 --> 00:18:47,249
Medicine Bow was my first,
and I took its dimensions,

346
00:18:47,249 --> 00:18:53,212
twenty-nine buildings in all⁠—one coal
shute, one water tank,

347
00:18:53,212 --> 00:18:59,015
the station, one store,
two eating-houses, one billiard hall,

348
00:18:59,015 --> 00:19:05,698
two tool-houses, one feed stable,
and twelve others that for one reason

349
00:19:05,698 --> 00:19:08,266
and another I shall not name.

350
00:19:08,266 --> 00:19:12,867
Yet this wretched husk of squalor spent
thought upon appearances;

351
00:19:12,867 --> 00:19:18,110
many houses in it wore a false front to
seem as if they were two stories high.

352
00:19:18,110 --> 00:19:23,438
There they stood, rearing their pitiful
masquerade amid a fringe of old tin

353
00:19:23,438 --> 00:19:29,380
cans, while at their very doors began a
world of crystal light,

354
00:19:29,380 --> 00:19:35,688
a land without end, a space across which
Noah and Adam might come

355
00:19:35,688 --> 00:19:37,563
straight from Genesis.

356
00:19:37,563 --> 00:19:42,621
Into that space went wandering a road,
over a hill and down out of sight,

357
00:19:42,621 --> 00:19:46,821
and up again smaller in the distance,
and down once more, and up once more,

358
00:19:46,821 --> -1:59:59,000
straining the eyes, and so away

359
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
.

360
00:19:49,781 --> 00:19:52,463
Then I heard a fellow greet my Virginian.

361
00:19:52,463 --> 00:19:56,452
He came rollicking out of a door,
and made a pass with his hand

362
00:19:56,452 --> -1:59:59,000
at the Virginian’s hat

363
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
.

364
00:19:58,627 --> 00:20:03,736
The Southerner dodged it,
and I saw once more the tiger undulation

365
00:20:03,736 --> 00:20:08,054
of body, and knew my escort was he of
the rope and the corral.

366
00:20:08,054 --> 00:20:09,222
“How are yu’ Steve?”

367
00:20:09,222 --> 00:20:11,616
he said to the rollicking man.

368
00:20:11,616 --> 00:20:16,924
And in his tone I heard
instantly old friendship speaking.

369
00:20:16,924 --> 00:20:20,038
With Steve he would take
and give familiarity.

370
00:20:20,038 --> 00:20:27,069
Steve looked at me, and looked away⁠—
and that was all.

371
00:20:27,069 --> 00:20:28,582
But it was enough.

372
00:20:28,582 --> 00:20:33,396
In no company had I ever felt
so much an outsider.

373
00:20:33,396 --> 00:20:36,802
Yet I liked the company,
and wished that it would like me.

374
00:20:36,802 --> 00:20:38,098
“Just come to town?”

375
00:20:38,098 --> 00:20:40,111
inquired Steve of the Virginian.

376
00:20:40,111 --> 00:20:42,082
“Been here since noon.

377
00:20:42,082 --> 00:20:43,602
Been waiting for the train.”

378
00:20:43,602 --> 00:20:44,624
“Going out tonight?”

379
00:20:44,624 --> 00:20:46,402
“I reckon I’ll pull out tomorro’.”

380
00:20:46,402 --> 00:20:48,533
“Beds are all took,” said Steve.

381
00:20:48,533 --> 00:20:50,853
This was for my benefit.

382
00:20:50,853 --> 00:20:53,070
“Dear me,” said I.

383
00:20:53,070 --> 00:20:56,566
“But I guess one of them drummers will
let yu’ double up with him.”

384
00:20:56,566 --> 00:20:58,880
Steve was enjoying himself, I think.

385
00:20:58,880 --> 00:21:03,418
He had his saddle and blankets,
and beds were nothing to him.

386
00:21:03,418 --> 00:21:06,182
“Drummers, are they?”

387
00:21:06,182 --> 00:21:07,393
asked the Virginian.

388
00:21:07,393 --> 00:21:13,755
“Two Jews handling cigars,
one American with consumption killer,

389
00:21:13,755 --> 00:21:16,455
and a Dutchman with jew’lry.”

390
00:21:16,455 --> 00:21:20,668
The Virginian set down my valise,
and seemed to meditate.

391
00:21:20,668 --> 00:21:24,448
“I did want a bed tonight,”
he murmured gently.

392
00:21:24,448 --> 00:21:28,651
“Well,” Steve suggested,
“the American looks like

393
00:21:28,651 --> 00:21:30,782
he washed the oftenest.”

394
00:21:30,782 --> 00:21:34,784
“That’s of no consequence to
me,” observed the Southerner.

395
00:21:34,784 --> 00:21:36,724
“Guess it’ll be when yu’ see ’em.”

396
00:21:36,724 --> 00:21:38,795
“Oh, I’m meaning something different.

397
00:21:38,795 --> 00:21:42,246
I wanted a bed to myself.”

398
00:21:42,246 --> 00:21:43,726
“Then you’ll have to build one.”

399
00:21:43,726 --> 00:21:45,581
“Bet yu’ I have the Dutchman’s.”

400
00:21:45,581 --> 00:21:47,066
“Take a man that won’t scare.

401
00:21:47,066 --> -1:59:59,000
Bet yu’ drinks yu’ can’t
have the American’s.

402
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

403
00:21:49,837 --> 00:21:52,900
“Go yu’ ” said the Virginian.

404
00:21:52,900 --> 00:21:56,191
“I’ll have his bed without any fuss.

405
00:21:56,191 --> 00:21:57,507
Drinks for the crowd.”

406
00:21:57,507 --> 00:22:01,413
“I suppose you have me beat,”
said Steve, grinning

407
00:22:01,413 --> 00:22:02,798
at him affectionately.

408
00:22:02,798 --> 00:22:06,601
“You’re such a son-of-a ⸻ when you
get down to work.

409
00:22:06,601 --> 00:22:07,641
Well, so long!

410
00:22:07,641 --> 00:22:10,054
I got to fix my horse’s hoofs.”

411
00:22:10,054 --> 00:22:12,675
I had expected that the man
would be struck down.

412
00:22:12,675 --> 00:22:17,243
He had used to the Virginian a term of
heaviest insult, I thought.

413
00:22:17,243 --> 00:22:23,171
I had marvelled to hear it come so
unheralded from Steve’s friendly lips.

414
00:22:23,171 --> 00:22:25,347
And now I marvelled still more.

415
00:22:25,347 --> 00:22:30,475
Evidently he had meant no harm by it,
and evidently no offence had been taken.

416
00:22:30,475 --> 00:22:34,678
Used thus, this language
was plainly complimentary.

417
00:22:34,678 --> 00:22:38,961
I had stepped into a world new to me
indeed, and novelties were occurring

418
00:22:38,961 --> 00:22:42,041
with scarce any time to
get breath between them.

419
00:22:42,041 --> 00:22:45,761
As to where I should sleep,
I had forgotten that problem

420
00:22:45,761 --> 00:22:48,062
altogether in my curiosity.

421
00:22:48,062 --> 00:22:50,354
What was the Virginian going to do now?

422
00:22:50,354 --> 00:22:54,496
I began to know that the quiet of
this man was volcanic.

423
00:22:54,496 --> 00:22:55,966
“Will you wash first, sir?”

424
00:22:55,966 --> 00:23:00,835
We were at the door of the eating-house,
and he set my valise inside.

425
00:23:00,835 --> 00:23:06,053
In my tenderfoot innocence I was looking
indoors for the washing arrangements.

426
00:23:06,053 --> 00:23:09,032
“It’s out hyeh, seh,”
he informed me gravely,

427
00:23:09,032 --> 00:23:11,102
but with strong Southern accent.

428
00:23:11,102 --> 00:23:15,547
Internal mirth seemed often to heighten
the local flavor of his speech.

429
00:23:15,547 --> 00:23:23,367
There were other times when it had scarce
any special accent or fault in grammar.

430
00:23:23,367 --> 00:23:27,007
A trough was to my right,
slippery with soapy water;

431
00:23:27,007 --> 00:23:31,499
and hanging from a roller above one end
of it was a rag of discouraging

432
00:23:31,499 --> 00:23:32,429
appearance.

433
00:23:32,429 --> 00:23:35,869
The Virginian caught it,
and it performed one whirling

434
00:23:35,869 --> 00:23:38,212
revolution on its roller.

435
00:23:38,212 --> 00:23:41,897
Not a dry or clean inch could
be found on it.

436
00:23:41,897 --> 00:23:45,015
He took off his hat, and put his
head in the door.

437
00:23:45,015 --> 00:23:48,552
“Your towel, ma’am,” said he,
“has been too popular.”

438
00:23:48,552 --> 00:23:51,160
She came out, a pretty woman.

439
00:23:51,160 --> 00:23:55,895
Her eyes rested upon him for a moment,
then upon me with disfavor;

440
00:23:55,895 --> 00:23:58,471
then they returned to his black hair.

441
00:23:58,471 --> 00:24:06,189
“The allowance is one a day,”
said she, very quietly.

442
00:24:06,189 --> 00:24:09,935
“But when folks are particular⁠—” She
completed her sentence by removing the

443
00:24:09,935 --> 00:24:13,019
old towel and giving a clean one to us.

444
00:24:13,019 --> 00:24:15,314
“Thank you, ma’am,” said the cowpuncher.

445
00:24:15,314 --> 00:24:20,121
She looked once more at his black hair,
and without any word returned to

446
00:24:20,121 --> 00:24:21,876
her guests at supper.

447
00:24:21,876 --> 00:24:26,742
A pail stood in the trough,
almost empty; and this he filled for

448
00:24:26,742 --> 00:24:28,914
me from a well.

449
00:24:28,914 --> 00:24:33,164
There was some soap sliding at large in
the trough, but I got my own.

450
00:24:33,164 --> 00:24:39,013
And then in a tin basin I removed as many
of the stains of travel as I was able.

451
00:24:39,013 --> 00:24:42,477
It was not much of a toilet that I made
in this first wash-trough of my

452
00:24:42,477 --> 00:24:47,211
experience, but it had to suffice,
and I took my seat at supper.

453
00:24:47,211 --> 00:24:50,539
Canned stuff it was⁠—corned beef.

454
00:24:50,539 --> 00:24:53,823
And one of my table companions said
the truth about it.

455
00:24:53,823 --> 00:24:57,572
“When I slung my teeth over that,”
he remarked, “I thought I

456
00:24:57,572 --> 00:24:59,494
was chewing a hammock.”

457
00:24:59,494 --> 00:25:03,027
We had strange coffee,
and condensed milk; and I have

458
00:25:03,027 --> 00:25:04,454
never seen more flies.

459
00:25:04,454 --> 00:25:07,158
I made no attempt to talk,
for no one in this country

460
00:25:07,158 --> 00:25:08,472
seemed favorable to me.

461
00:25:08,472 --> 00:25:12,978
By reason of something⁠—my clothes,
my hat, my pronunciation,

462
00:25:12,978 --> 00:25:15,538
whatever it might be,
I possessed the secret of

463
00:25:15,538 --> 00:25:17,500
estranging people at sight.

464
00:25:17,500 --> 00:25:21,710
Yet I was doing better than I knew;
my strict silence and attention to the

465
00:25:21,710 --> 00:25:26,138
corned beef made me in the eyes of the
cowboys at table compare well with the

466
00:25:26,138 --> 00:25:28,639
over-talkative commercial travellers.

467
00:25:28,639 --> 00:25:32,110
The Virginian’s entrance
produced a slight silence.

468
00:25:32,110 --> 00:25:38,437
He had done wonders with the wash-trough,
and he had somehow brushed his clothes.

469
00:25:38,437 --> 00:25:42,162
With all the roughness of his dress,
he was now the neatest of us.

470
00:25:42,162 --> 00:25:47,148
He nodded to some of the other cowboys,
and began his meal in quiet.

471
00:25:47,148 --> 00:25:50,381
But silence is not the native
element of the drummer.

472
00:25:50,381 --> 00:25:53,951
An average fish can go a longer time out
of water than this breed

473
00:25:53,951 --> 00:25:55,945
can live without talking.

474
00:25:55,945 --> 00:26:01,131
One of them now looked across the table
at the grave, flannel-shirted Virginian;

475
00:26:01,131 --> 00:26:06,484
he inspected, and came to the imprudent
conclusion that he understood his man.

476
00:26:06,484 --> 00:26:09,280
“Good evening,” he said briskly.

477
00:26:09,280 --> 00:26:11,289
“Good evening,” said the Virginian.

478
00:26:11,289 --> 00:26:12,857
“Just come to town?”

479
00:26:12,857 --> 00:26:14,097
pursued the drummer.

480
00:26:14,097 --> 00:26:17,993
“Just come to town,” the
Virginian suavely assented.

481
00:26:17,993 --> 00:26:20,191
“Cattle business jumping along?”

482
00:26:20,191 --> 00:26:21,612
inquired the drummer.

483
00:26:21,612 --> 00:26:22,427
“Oh, fair.”

484
00:26:22,427 --> 00:26:24,900
And the Virginian took
some more corned beef.

485
00:26:24,900 --> 00:26:28,615
“Gets a move on your appetite,
anyway,” suggested the drummer.

486
00:26:28,615 --> 00:26:30,871
The Virginian drank some coffee.

487
00:26:30,871 --> 00:26:37,020
Presently the pretty woman refilled his
cup without his asking her.

488
00:26:37,020 --> 00:26:40,571
“Guess I’ve met you before,”
the drummer stated next.

489
00:26:40,571 --> 00:26:43,108
The Virginian glanced at him
for a brief moment.

490
00:26:43,108 --> 00:26:44,301
“Haven’t I, now?

491
00:26:44,301 --> 00:26:45,623
Ain’t I seen you somewhere?

492
00:26:45,623 --> 00:26:46,336
Look at me.

493
00:26:46,336 --> 00:26:48,824
You been in Chicago, ain’t you?

494
00:26:48,824 --> 00:26:50,451
You look at me well.

495
00:26:50,451 --> -1:59:59,000
Remember Ikey’s, don’t you?

496
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

497
00:26:54,056 --> 00:26:55,779
“I don’t reckon I do.”

498
00:26:55,779 --> 00:26:57,305
“See, now!

499
00:26:57,305 --> 00:26:59,437
I knowed you’d been in Chicago.

500
00:26:59,437 --> 00:27:01,637
Four or five years ago.

501
00:27:01,637 --> 00:27:03,807
Or maybe it’s two years.

502
00:27:03,807 --> 00:27:05,688
Time’s nothing to me.

503
00:27:05,688 --> 00:27:08,025
But I never forget a face.

504
00:27:08,025 --> 00:27:09,528
Yes, sir.

505
00:27:09,528 --> 00:27:11,693
Him and me’s met at Ikey’s, all right.”

506
00:27:11,693 --> 00:27:14,959
This important point the drummer stated
to all of us.

507
00:27:14,959 --> 00:27:19,439
We were called to witness how well he
had proved old acquaintanceship.

508
00:27:19,439 --> 00:27:21,587
“Ain’t the world small, though!”

509
00:27:21,587 --> 00:27:23,419
he exclaimed complacently.

510
00:27:23,419 --> 00:27:27,428
“Meet a man once and you’re sure to run
on to him again.

511
00:27:27,428 --> 00:27:28,659
That’s straight.

512
00:27:28,659 --> 00:27:30,579
That’s no barroom josh.”

513
00:27:30,579 --> 00:27:34,311
And the drummer’s eye included us
all in his confidence.

514
00:27:34,311 --> 00:27:37,951
I wondered if he had attained that high
perfection when a man

515
00:27:37,951 --> 00:27:40,065
believes his own lies.

516
00:27:40,065 --> 00:27:43,049
The Virginian did not seem interested.

517
00:27:43,049 --> 00:27:47,142
He placidly attended to his food,
while our landlady moved between dining

518
00:27:47,142 --> 00:27:49,216
room and kitchen, and
the drummer expanded.

519
00:27:49,216 --> 00:27:50,279
“Yes, sir!

520
00:27:50,279 --> 00:27:54,237
Ikey’s over by the stockyards,
patronized by all cattlemen

521
00:27:54,237 --> 00:27:55,803
that know what’s what.

522
00:27:55,803 --> 00:27:56,563
That’s where.

523
00:27:56,563 --> 00:27:58,243
Maybe it’s three years.

524
00:27:58,243 --> 00:28:02,102
Time never was nothing to me.

525
00:28:02,102 --> 00:28:03,599
But faces!

526
00:28:03,599 --> 00:28:05,137
Why, I can’t quit ’em.

527
00:28:05,137 --> 00:28:10,951
Adults or children, male and female;
onced I seen ’em I couldn’t lose one off

528
00:28:10,951 --> 00:28:16,411
my memory, not if you were to pay me
bounty, five dollars a face.

529
00:28:16,411 --> 00:28:18,670
White men, that is.

530
00:28:18,670 --> 00:28:22,604
Can’t do nothing with niggers or Chinese.

531
00:28:22,604 --> 00:28:24,132
But you’re white, all right.”

532
00:28:24,132 --> 00:28:27,947
The drummer suddenly returned to the
Virginian with this high compliment.

533
00:28:27,947 --> 00:28:32,432
The cowpuncher had taken out a pipe,
and was slowly rubbing it.

534
00:28:32,432 --> 00:28:36,859
The compliment seemed to escape his
attention, and the drummer went on.

535
00:28:36,859 --> 00:28:41,023
“I can tell a man when he’s white,
put him at Ikey’s or out loose

536
00:28:41,023 --> 00:28:42,463
here in the sagebrush.”

537
00:28:42,463 --> 00:28:46,644
And he rolled a cigar across
to the Virginian’s plate.

538
00:28:46,644 --> 00:28:48,334
“Selling them?”

539
00:28:48,334 --> 00:28:51,516
inquired the Virginian.

540
00:28:51,516 --> 00:28:55,098
“Solid goods, my friend.

541
00:28:55,098 --> 00:29:01,380
Havana wrappers, the biggest tobacco
proposition for five cents got out yet.

542
00:29:01,380 --> 00:29:06,242
Take it, try it, light it, watch it burn.

543
00:29:06,242 --> 00:29:06,732
Here.”

544
00:29:06,732 --> 00:29:08,865
And he held out a bunch of matches.

545
00:29:08,865 --> 00:29:11,917
The Virginian tossed a five-cent
piece over to him.

546
00:29:11,917 --> 00:29:13,880
“Oh, no, my friend!

547
00:29:13,880 --> 00:29:15,540
Not from you!

548
00:29:15,540 --> 00:29:17,091
Not after Ikey’s.

549
00:29:17,091 --> 00:29:18,772
I don’t forget you.

550
00:29:18,772 --> 00:29:21,073
See?

551
00:29:21,073 --> 00:29:26,486
I knowed your face right away.

552
00:29:26,486 --> 00:29:29,353
See?

553
00:29:29,353 --> 00:29:30,576
That’s straight.

554
00:29:30,576 --> 00:29:32,625
I seen you at Chicago all right.”

555
00:29:32,625 --> 00:29:35,688
“Maybe you did,” said the Virginian.

556
00:29:35,688 --> 00:29:38,037
“Sometimes I’m mighty careless
what I look at.”

557
00:29:38,037 --> 00:29:39,571
“Well, py damn!”

558
00:29:39,571 --> 00:29:42,361
now exclaimed the Dutch
drummer, hilariously.

559
00:29:42,361 --> 00:29:44,631
“I am ploom disappointed.

560
00:29:44,631 --> 00:29:47,711
I vas hoping to sell him
somedings myself.”

561
00:29:47,711 --> 00:29:51,014
“Not the same here,” stated the American.

562
00:29:51,014 --> 00:29:53,415
“He’s too healthy for me.

563
00:29:53,415 --> 00:29:55,087
I gave him up on sight.”

564
00:29:55,087 --> 00:29:59,175
Now it was the American drummer whose bed
the Virginian had in his eye.

565
00:29:59,175 --> 00:30:02,055
This was a sensible man,
and had talked less than his

566
00:30:02,055 --> 00:30:03,375
brothers in the trade.

567
00:30:03,375 --> 00:30:06,625
I had little doubt who would end by
sleeping in his bed;

568
00:30:06,625 --> 00:30:10,901
but how the thing would be done
interested me more deeply than ever.

569
00:30:10,901 --> 00:30:15,207
The Virginian looked amiably at his
intended victim, and made one or two

570
00:30:15,207 --> 00:30:18,209
remarks regarding patent medicines.

571
00:30:18,209 --> 00:30:22,000
There must be a good deal of money in
them, he supposed, with a live

572
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:23,263
man to manage them.

573
00:30:23,263 --> 00:30:25,023
The victim was flattered.

574
00:30:25,023 --> 00:30:28,340
No other person at the table had been
favored with so much of

575
00:30:28,340 --> 00:30:30,772
the tall cowpuncher’s notice.

576
00:30:30,772 --> 00:30:33,797
He responded, and they
had a pleasant talk.

577
00:30:33,797 --> 00:30:38,063
I did not divine that the Virginian’s
genius was even then at work,

578
00:30:38,063 --> 00:30:41,448
and that all this was part
of his satanic strategy.

579
00:30:41,448 --> 00:30:43,936
But Steve must have divined it.

580
00:30:43,936 --> 00:30:48,594
For while a few of us still sat finishing
our supper, that facetious horseman

581
00:30:48,594 --> 00:30:52,554
returned from doctoring his horse’s
hoofs, put his head into the dining

582
00:30:52,554 --> 00:30:57,847
room, took in the way in which the
Virginian was engaging his victim in

583
00:30:57,847 --> 00:31:01,504
conversation, remarked
aloud, “I’ve lost!”

584
00:31:01,504 --> 00:31:03,079
and closed the door again.

585
00:31:03,079 --> 00:31:04,209
“What’s he lost?”

586
00:31:04,209 --> 00:31:05,989
inquired the American drummer.

587
00:31:05,989 --> 00:31:09,241
“Oh, you mustn’t mind
him,” drawled the Virginian.

588
00:31:09,241 --> 00:31:13,229
“He’s one of those box-head jokers goes
around openin’ and shuttin’

589
00:31:13,229 --> 00:31:14,149
doors that-a-way.

590
00:31:14,149 --> 00:31:15,808
We call him harmless.

591
00:31:15,808 --> 00:31:19,337
Well,” he broke off, “I
reckon I’ll go smoke.

592
00:31:19,337 --> 00:31:20,712
Not allowed in hyeh?”

593
00:31:20,712 --> 00:31:25,069
This last he addressed to the
landlady, with especial gentleness.

594
00:31:25,069 --> 00:31:29,567
She shook her head, and her eyes followed
him as he went out.

595
00:31:29,567 --> 00:31:34,905
Left to myself I meditated for some time
upon my lodging for the night,

596
00:31:34,905 --> 00:31:38,567
and smoked a cigar for consolation
as I walked about.

597
00:31:38,567 --> 00:31:43,127
It was not a hotel that we had supped in.

598
00:31:43,127 --> 00:31:46,674
Hotel at Medicine Bow there
appeared to be none.

599
00:31:46,674 --> 00:31:52,960
But connected with the eating-house was
that place where, according to Steve,

600
00:31:52,960 --> 00:31:57,941
the beds were all taken,
and there I went to see for myself.

601
00:31:57,941 --> 00:31:59,154
Steve had spoken the truth.

602
00:31:59,154 --> 00:32:04,751
It was a single apartment containing four
or five beds, and nothing else whatever.

603
00:32:04,751 --> 00:32:09,700
And when I looked at these beds,
my sorrow that I could sleep in none

604
00:32:09,700 --> 00:32:11,111
of them grew less.

605
00:32:11,111 --> 00:32:15,111
To be alone in one offered no temptation,
and as for this courtesy of the

606
00:32:15,111 --> 00:32:19,445
country, this doubling up⁠—!

607
00:32:19,445 --> 00:32:21,577
“Well, they have got ahead of us.”

608
00:32:21,577 --> 00:32:23,697
This was the Virginian
standing at my elbow.

609
00:32:23,697 --> 00:32:24,758
I assented.

610
00:32:24,758 --> 00:32:28,059
“They have staked out
their claims,” he added.

611
00:32:28,059 --> 00:32:32,932
In this public sleeping room they had
done what one does to secure a seat

612
00:32:32,932 --> 00:32:37,132
in a railroad train.

613
00:32:38,916 --> 00:32:50,282
Upon each bed, as notice of occupancy,
lay some article of travel or of dress.

614
00:32:50,282 --> 00:32:55,687
As we stood there, the two Jews came in
and opened and arranged their valises,

615
00:32:55,687 --> 00:32:59,727
and folded and refolded
their linen dusters.

616
00:32:59,727 --> 00:33:03,810
Then a railroad employee entered and
began to go to bed at this hour,

617
00:33:03,810 --> 00:33:06,368
before dusk had wholly
darkened into night.

618
00:33:06,368 --> 00:33:11,117
For him, going to bed meant removing his
boots and placing his overalls and

619
00:33:11,117 --> 00:33:12,683
waistcoat beneath his pillow.

620
00:33:12,683 --> 00:33:14,134
He had no coat.

621
00:33:14,134 --> 00:33:18,043
His work began at three in the morning;
and even as we still talked

622
00:33:18,043 --> 00:33:19,357
he began to snore.

623
00:33:19,357 --> 00:33:22,677
“The man that keeps the store is a friend
of mine,” said the Virginian;

624
00:33:22,677 --> 00:33:25,237
“and you can be pretty near
comfortable on his counter.

625
00:33:25,237 --> 00:33:26,677
Got any blankets?”

626
00:33:26,677 --> 00:33:28,215
I had no blankets.

627
00:33:28,215 --> 00:33:29,427
“Looking for a bed?”

628
00:33:29,427 --> 00:33:32,065
inquired the American
drummer, now arriving.

629
00:33:32,065 --> 00:33:37,338
“Yes, he’s looking for a bed,”
answered the voice of Steve behind him.

630
00:33:37,338 --> 00:33:41,199
“Seems a waste of time,”
observed the Virginian.

631
00:33:41,199 --> 00:33:43,717
He looked thoughtfully from
one bed to another.

632
00:33:43,717 --> 00:33:46,171
“I didn’t know I’d have to lay over here.

633
00:33:46,171 --> 00:33:48,123
Well, I have sat up before.”

634
00:33:48,123 --> 00:33:51,589
“This one’s mine,” said the drummer,
sitting down on it.

635
00:33:51,589 --> 00:33:54,126
“Half’s plenty enough room for me.”

636
00:33:54,126 --> 00:33:57,182
“You’re cert’nly mighty
kind,” said the cowpuncher.

637
00:33:57,182 --> 00:34:00,053
“But I’d not think o’
disconveniencing yu’.”

638
00:34:00,053 --> 00:34:01,705
“That’s nothing.

639
00:34:01,705 --> 00:34:04,534
The other half is yours.

640
00:34:04,534 --> 00:34:06,814
Turn in right now if you feel like it.”

641
00:34:06,814 --> 00:34:07,961
“No.

642
00:34:07,961 --> 00:34:10,822
I don’t reckon I’ll turn in right now.

643
00:34:10,822 --> 00:34:12,785
Better keep your bed to yourself.”

644
00:34:12,785 --> 00:34:17,026
“See here,” urged the drummer,
“if I take you I’m safe from drawing

645
00:34:17,026 --> 00:34:19,458
some party I might not
care so much about.

646
00:34:19,458 --> 00:34:22,882
This here sleeping proposition
is a lottery.”

647
00:34:22,882 --> 00:34:27,654
“Well,” said the Virginian (and his
hesitation was truly masterly),

648
00:34:27,654 --> 00:34:29,485
“if you put it that way⁠—”

649
00:34:29,485 --> 00:34:30,411
“I do put it that way.

650
00:34:30,411 --> 00:34:32,638
Why, you’re clean!

651
00:34:32,638 --> 00:34:35,198
You’ve had a shave right now.

652
00:34:35,198 --> 00:34:38,672
You turn in when you feel
inclined, old man!

653
00:34:38,672 --> 00:34:40,349
I ain’t retiring just yet.”

654
00:34:40,349 --> 00:34:44,140
The drummer had struck a slightly false
note in these last remarks.

655
00:34:44,140 --> 00:34:46,749
He should not have said “old man.”

656
00:34:46,749 --> 00:34:52,990
Until this I had thought him merely an
amiable person who wished to do a favor.

657
00:34:52,990 --> 00:34:55,439
But “old man” came in wrong.

658
00:34:55,439 --> 00:34:59,795
It had a hateful taint of his profession;
the being too soon with everybody,

659
00:34:59,795 --> 00:35:03,655
the celluloid good-fellowship that
passes for ivory with nine in ten

660
00:35:03,655 --> 00:35:04,796
of the city crowd.

661
00:35:04,796 --> 00:35:08,533
But not so with the sons of the sagebrush.

662
00:35:08,533 --> 00:35:12,760
They live nearer nature,
and they know better.

663
00:35:12,760 --> 00:35:17,668
But the Virginian blandly accepted “old
man” from his victim:

664
00:35:17,668 --> 00:35:18,847
he had a game to play.

665
00:35:18,847 --> 00:35:22,478
“Well, I cert’nly thank yu’,” he said.

666
00:35:22,478 --> 00:35:25,614
“After a while I’ll take advantage
of your kind offer.”

667
00:35:25,614 --> 00:35:26,830
I was surprised.

668
00:35:26,830 --> 00:35:31,507
Possession being nine points of the law,
it seemed his very chance to intrench

669
00:35:31,507 --> 00:35:33,405
himself in the bed.

670
00:35:33,405 --> 00:35:37,612
But the cowpuncher had planned a
campaign needing no intrenchments.

671
00:35:37,612 --> 00:35:42,452
Moreover, going to bed before nine
o’clock upon the first evening in many

672
00:35:42,452 --> 00:35:46,972
weeks that a town’s resources were open
to you, would be a dull proceeding.

673
00:35:46,972 --> 00:35:51,672
Our entire company, drummer and all,
now walked over to the store,

674
00:35:51,672 --> 00:35:55,198
and here my sleeping
arrangements were made easily.

675
00:35:55,198 --> 00:36:00,019
This store was the cleanest place and the
best in Medicine Bow,

676
00:36:00,019 --> 00:36:03,896
and would have been a good store
anywhere, offering a multitude of things

677
00:36:03,896 --> 00:36:06,989
for sale, and kept by
a very civil proprietor.

678
00:36:06,989 --> 00:36:09,828
He bade me make myself at home,
and placed both of his

679
00:36:09,828 --> 00:36:11,696
counters at my disposal.

680
00:36:11,696 --> 00:36:16,702
Upon the grocery side there stood a
cheese too large and strong to sleep

681
00:36:16,702 --> 00:36:20,215
near comfortably, and I therefore chose
the dry-goods side.

682
00:36:20,215 --> 00:36:25,688
Here thick quilts were unrolled for me,
to make it soft; and no condition was

683
00:36:25,688 --> 00:36:30,013
placed upon me, further than that I
should remove my boots,

684
00:36:30,013 --> 00:36:35,168
because the quilts were new,
and clean, and for sale.

685
00:36:35,168 --> 00:36:37,714
So now my rest was assured.

686
00:36:37,714 --> 00:36:41,788
Not an anxiety remained in my thoughts.

687
00:36:41,788 --> 00:36:47,346
These therefore turned themselves wholly
to the other man’s bed,

688
00:36:47,346 --> 00:36:49,431
and how he was going to lose it.

689
00:36:49,431 --> 00:36:52,631
I think that Steve was more
curious even than myself.

690
00:36:52,631 --> 00:36:54,020
Time was on the wing.

691
00:36:54,020 --> 00:37:00,142
His bet must be decided,
and the drinks enjoyed.

692
00:37:00,142 --> 00:37:04,487
He stood against the grocery
counter, contemplating the Virginian.

693
00:37:04,487 --> 00:37:06,732
But it was to me that he spoke.

694
00:37:06,732 --> 00:37:10,062
The Virginian, however,
listened to every word.

695
00:37:10,062 --> 00:37:12,353
“Your first visit to this country?”

696
00:37:12,353 --> 00:37:14,848
I told him yes.

697
00:37:14,848 --> 00:37:16,104
“How do you like it?”

698
00:37:16,104 --> 00:37:18,294
I expected to like it very much.

699
00:37:18,294 --> 00:37:20,244
“How does the climate strike you?”

700
00:37:20,244 --> 00:37:22,023
I thought the climate was fine.

701
00:37:22,023 --> 00:37:23,557
“Makes a man thirsty though.”

702
00:37:23,557 --> 00:37:26,762
This was the sub-current which the
Virginian plainly looked for.

703
00:37:26,762 --> 00:37:30,296
But he, like Steve, addressed
himself to me.

704
00:37:30,296 --> 00:37:35,280
“Yes,” he put in, “thirsty while
a man’s soft yet.

705
00:37:35,280 --> -1:59:59,000
You’ll harden.

706
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

707
00:37:36,763 --> 00:37:39,971
“I guess you’ll find it a drier country
than you were given to

708
00:37:39,971 --> 00:37:42,422
expect,” said Steve.

709
00:37:42,422 --> 00:37:46,818
“If your habits have been frequent that
way,” said the Virginian.

710
00:37:46,818 --> 00:37:50,653
“There’s parts of Wyoming,”
pursued Steve, “where you’ll go hours

711
00:37:50,653 --> -1:59:59,000
and hours before you’ll see
a drop of wetness.

712
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

713
00:37:53,623 --> 00:37:58,330
“And if yu’ keep a-thinkin’ about it,”
said the Virginian, “it’ll seem

714
00:37:58,330 --> 00:38:00,743
like days and days.”

715
00:38:00,743 --> 00:38:04,913
Steve, at this stroke,
gave up, and clapped him on the shoulder

716
00:38:04,913 --> 00:38:06,115
with a joyous chuckle.

717
00:38:06,115 --> 00:38:08,129
“You old son-of-a ⸻!”

718
00:38:08,129 --> 00:38:09,558
he cried affectionately.

719
00:38:09,558 --> 00:38:12,623
“Drinks are due now,” said the Virginian.

720
00:38:12,623 --> 00:38:14,331
“My treat, Steve.

721
00:38:14,331 --> 00:38:17,808
But I reckon your suspense will have to
linger a while yet.”

722
00:38:17,808 --> 00:38:22,418
Thus they dropped into direct talk from
that speech of the fourth dimension

723
00:38:22,418 --> 00:38:24,287
where they had been using
me for their telephone.

724
00:38:24,287 --> 00:38:26,238
“Any cyards going tonight?”

725
00:38:26,238 --> 00:38:27,668
inquired the Virginian.

726
00:38:27,668 --> 00:38:32,496
“Stud and draw,” Steve told him.

727
00:38:32,496 --> -1:59:59,000
“Strangers playing.

728
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

729
00:38:36,016 --> 00:38:40,236
“I think I’d like to get into a game for
a while,” said the Southerner.

730
00:38:40,236 --> 00:38:41,756
“Strangers, yu’ say?”

731
00:38:41,756 --> 00:38:45,299
And then, before quitting the store,
he made his toilet for this

732
00:38:45,299 --> 00:38:46,529
little hand at poker.

733
00:38:46,529 --> 00:38:48,399
It was a simple preparation.

734
00:38:48,399 --> 00:38:52,159
He took his pistol from its holster,
examined it, then shoved it between his

735
00:38:52,159 --> 00:38:56,200
overalls and his shirt in front,
and pulled his waistcoat over it.

736
00:38:56,200 --> 00:38:59,881
He might have been combing his hair for
all the attention anyone paid

737
00:38:59,881 --> 00:39:01,985
to this, except myself.

738
00:39:01,985 --> 00:39:06,081
Then the two friends went out,
and I bethought me of that epithet which

739
00:39:06,081 --> 00:39:10,201
Steve again had used to the Virginian as
he clapped him on the shoulder.

740
00:39:10,201 --> 00:39:15,583
Clearly this wild country spoke a
language other than mine⁠—the word here

741
00:39:15,583 --> 00:39:17,248
was a term of endearment.

742
00:39:17,248 --> 00:39:19,605
Such was my conclusion.

743
00:39:19,605 --> 00:39:22,583
The drummers had finished their dealings
with the proprietor,

744
00:39:22,583 --> 00:39:26,063
and they were gossiping together in a
knot by the door as the

745
00:39:26,063 --> 00:39:27,451
Virginian passed out.

746
00:39:27,451 --> 00:39:28,903
“See you later, old man!”

747
00:39:28,903 --> 00:39:32,503
This was the American drummer
accosting his prospective bedfellow.

748
00:39:32,503 --> 00:39:36,510
“Oh, yes,” returned the
bedfellow, and was gone.

749
00:39:36,510 --> 00:39:44,907
The American drummer winked
triumphantly at his brethren.

750
00:39:45,049 --> 00:39:49,175
“He’s all right,” he observed,
jerking a thumb after the Virginian.

751
00:39:49,175 --> 00:39:50,245
“He’s easy.

752
00:39:50,245 --> 00:39:53,168
You got to know him to work him.

753
00:39:53,168 --> -1:59:59,000
That’s all.

754
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

755
00:39:54,568 --> 00:39:57,087
“Und vat is your point?”

756
00:39:57,087 --> 00:39:58,949
inquired the German drummer.

757
00:39:58,949 --> 00:40:03,194
“Point is⁠—he’ll not take any goods off
you or me; but he’s going to talk up the

758
00:40:03,194 --> 00:40:05,961
killer to any consumptive he runs
across.

759
00:40:05,961 --> 00:40:07,292
I ain’t done with him yet.

760
00:40:07,292 --> 00:40:11,106
Say,” (he now addressed the
proprietor), “what’s her name?”

761
00:40:11,106 --> 00:40:11,837
“Whose name?”

762
00:40:11,837 --> 00:40:13,513
“Woman runs the eating-house.”

763
00:40:13,513 --> 00:40:14,065
“Glen.

764
00:40:14,065 --> 00:40:14,473
Mrs.

765
00:40:14,473 --> 00:40:15,006
Glen.”

766
00:40:15,006 --> 00:40:16,073
“Ain’t she new?”

767
00:40:16,073 --> 00:40:17,710
“Been settled here about a month.

768
00:40:17,710 --> 00:40:19,553
Husband’s a freight conductor.”

769
00:40:19,553 --> 00:40:21,319
“Thought I’d not seen her before.

770
00:40:21,319 --> 00:40:22,747
She’s a good-looker.”

771
00:40:22,747 --> 00:40:23,274
“Hm!

772
00:40:23,274 --> 00:40:24,064
Yes.

773
00:40:24,064 --> 00:40:28,125
The kind of good looks I’d sooner see in
another man’s wife than mine.”

774
00:40:28,125 --> 00:40:30,318
“So that’s the gait, is it?”

775
00:40:30,318 --> 00:40:30,848
“Hm!

776
00:40:30,848 --> 00:40:33,226
well, it don’t seem to be.

777
00:40:33,226 --> 00:40:35,557
She come here with that reputation.

778
00:40:35,557 --> 00:40:38,027
But there’s been general disappointment.”

779
00:40:38,027 --> 00:40:40,598
“Then she ain’t lacked suitors any?”

780
00:40:40,598 --> 00:40:41,597
“Lacked!

781
00:40:41,597 --> 00:40:44,077
Are you acquainted with cowboys?”

782
00:40:44,077 --> 00:40:46,639
“And she disappointed ’em?

783
00:40:46,639 --> 00:40:48,815
Maybe she likes her husband?”

784
00:40:48,815 --> 00:40:49,335
“Hm!

785
00:40:49,335 --> -1:59:59,000
well, how are you to tell
about them silent kind?

786
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

787
00:40:52,989 --> 00:40:55,845
“Talking of conductors,”
began the drummer.

788
00:40:55,845 --> 00:41:01,296
And we listened to his anecdote.

789
00:41:03,898 --> 00:41:08,599
It was successful with his audience;
but when he launched fluently upon a

790
00:41:08,599 --> 00:41:11,055
second I strolled out.

791
00:41:11,055 --> 00:41:14,753
There was not enough wit in this narrator
to relieve his indecency,

792
00:41:14,753 --> 00:41:18,920
and I felt shame at having been
surprised into laughing with him.

793
00:41:18,920 --> 00:41:23,002
I left that company growing confidential
over their leering stories,

794
00:41:23,002 --> 00:41:24,545
and I sought the saloon.

795
00:41:24,545 --> 00:41:27,241
It was very quiet and orderly.

796
00:41:27,241 --> 00:41:32,986
Beer in quart bottles at a dollar I had
never met before; but saving its price,

797
00:41:32,986 --> 00:41:35,154
I found no complaint to make of it.

798
00:41:35,154 --> 00:41:40,884
Through folding doors I passed from the
bar proper with its bottles and elk head

799
00:41:40,884 --> 00:41:43,519
back to the hall with its various
tables.

800
00:41:43,519 --> 00:41:49,155
I saw a man sliding cards from a case,
and across the table from him another

801
00:41:49,155 --> 00:41:51,043
man laying counters down.

802
00:41:51,043 --> 00:41:56,640
Near by was a second dealer pulling cards
from the bottom of a pack,

803
00:41:56,640 --> 00:42:02,646
and opposite him a solemn old rustic
piling and changing coins upon the cards

804
00:42:02,646 --> 00:42:04,419
which lay already exposed.

805
00:42:04,419 --> 00:42:09,380
But now I heard a voice that drew my eyes
to the far corner of the room.

806
00:42:09,380 --> 00:42:11,073
“Why didn’t you stay in Arizona?”

807
00:42:11,073 --> 00:42:14,012
Harmless looking words as I
write them down here.

808
00:42:14,012 --> 00:42:19,960
Yet at the sound of them I noticed the
eyes of the others directed

809
00:42:19,960 --> 00:42:20,961
to that corner.

810
00:42:20,961 --> 00:42:26,889
What answer was given to them I did not
hear, nor did I see who spoke.

811
00:42:26,889 --> 00:42:28,759
Then came another remark.

812
00:42:28,759 --> 00:42:32,234
“Well, Arizona’s no place for amatures.”

813
00:42:32,234 --> 00:42:36,714
This time the two card dealers that I
stood near began to give a part of their

814
00:42:36,714 --> 00:42:39,787
attention to the group that
sat in the corner.

815
00:42:39,787 --> 00:42:44,827
There was in me a desire
to leave this room.

816
00:42:44,827 --> 00:42:50,684
So far my hours at Medicine Bow had
seemed to glide beneath a sunshine of

817
00:42:50,684 --> 00:42:53,720
merriment, of easygoing jocularity.

818
00:42:53,720 --> 00:42:57,244
This was suddenly gone,
like the wind changing to north in the

819
00:42:57,244 --> 00:42:58,742
middle of a warm day.

820
00:42:58,742 --> 00:43:01,797
But I stayed, being ashamed to go.

821
00:43:01,797 --> 00:43:06,698
Five or six players sat over in the
corner at a round table

822
00:43:06,698 --> 00:43:08,125
where counters were piled.

823
00:43:08,125 --> 00:43:12,612
Their eyes were close upon their cards,
and one seemed to be dealing a card at a

824
00:43:12,612 --> 00:43:16,454
time to each, with pauses
and betting between.

825
00:43:16,454 --> 00:43:21,706
Steve was there and the Virginian;
the others were new faces.

826
00:43:21,706 --> 00:43:26,431
“No place for amatures,”
repeated the voice; and now I saw that

827
00:43:26,431 --> 00:43:27,546
it was the dealer’s.

828
00:43:27,546 --> 00:43:32,763
There was in his countenance the same
ugliness that his words conveyed.

829
00:43:32,763 --> 00:43:34,013
“Who’s that talkin’?”

830
00:43:34,013 --> 00:43:36,995
said one of the men near me,
in a low voice.

831
00:43:36,995 --> 00:43:37,555
“Trampas.”

832
00:43:37,555 --> 00:43:38,860
“What’s he?”

833
00:43:38,860 --> 00:43:43,376
“Cowpuncher, broncobuster,
tin-horn, most anything.”

834
00:43:43,376 --> 00:43:44,494
“Who’s he talkin’ at?”

835
00:43:44,494 --> 00:43:48,275
“Think it’s the black-headed
guy he’s talking at.”

836
00:43:48,275 --> 00:43:50,815
“That ain’t supposed to be safe, is it?”

837
00:43:50,815 --> 00:43:53,784
“Guess we’re all goin’ to find out
in a few minutes.”

838
00:43:53,784 --> 00:43:55,478
“Been trouble between ’em?”

839
00:43:55,478 --> 00:43:56,815
“They’ve not met before.

840
00:43:56,815 --> 00:44:00,475
Trampas don’t enjoy losin’ to a stranger.”

841
00:44:00,475 --> 00:44:02,600
“Fello’s from Arizona, yu’ say?”

842
00:44:02,600 --> 00:44:03,795
“No.

843
00:44:03,795 --> 00:44:05,970
Virginia.

844
00:44:05,970 --> 00:44:09,988
He’s recently back from havin’
a look at Arizona.

845
00:44:09,988 --> 00:44:13,242
Went down there last year for a change.

846
00:44:13,242 --> 00:44:15,061
Works for the Sunk Creek outfit.”

847
00:44:15,061 --> 00:44:19,533
And then the dealer lowered his voice
still further and said something in the

848
00:44:19,533 --> 00:44:22,158
other man’s ear, causing him to grin.

849
00:44:22,158 --> 00:44:24,871
After which both of them looked at me.

850
00:44:24,871 --> 00:44:27,775
There had been silence over in the
corner; but now the man

851
00:44:27,775 --> 00:44:29,295
Trampas spoke again.

852
00:44:29,295 --> 00:44:36,574
“And ten,” said he, sliding out some
chips from before him.

853
00:44:36,574 --> 00:44:40,328
Very strange it was to hear him,
how he contrived to make those

854
00:44:40,328 --> 00:44:42,374
words a personal taunt.

855
00:44:42,374 --> 00:44:46,567
The Virginian was looking at his cards.

856
00:44:46,567 --> 00:44:48,011
He might have been deaf.

857
00:44:48,011 --> 00:44:50,769
“And twenty,” said the
next player, easily.

858
00:44:50,769 --> 00:44:53,360
The next threw his cards down.

859
00:44:53,360 --> 00:44:57,141
It was now the Virginian’s turn to bet,
or leave the game, and he did

860
00:44:57,141 --> 00:44:58,611
not speak at once.

861
00:44:58,611 --> 00:45:00,973
Therefore Trampas spoke.

862
00:45:00,973 --> 00:45:03,397
“Your bet, you son-of-a ⸻.”

863
00:45:03,397 --> 00:45:06,465
The Virginian’s pistol came out,
and his hand lay on the

864
00:45:06,465 --> 00:45:08,292
table, holding it unaimed.

865
00:45:08,292 --> 00:45:12,616
And with a voice as gentle as ever,
the voice that sounded almost like a

866
00:45:12,616 --> 00:45:17,195
caress, but drawling a very little more
than usual, so that there was almost a

867
00:45:17,195 --> 00:45:20,235
space between each word,
he issued his orders

868
00:45:20,235 --> 00:45:21,355
to the man Trampas:⁠—

869
00:45:21,355 --> 00:45:23,581
“When you call me that, smile.”

870
00:45:23,581 --> 00:45:26,606
And he looked at Trampas across the table.

871
00:45:26,606 --> 00:45:29,006
Yes, the voice was gentle.

872
00:45:29,006 --> 00:45:33,066
But in my ears it seemed as if somewhere
the bell of death was ringing;

873
00:45:33,066 --> 00:45:36,692
and silence, like a stroke,
fell on the large room.

874
00:45:36,692 --> 00:45:44,224
All men present, as if by some magnetic
current, had become aware of this

875
00:45:44,224 --> 00:45:45,286
crisis.

876
00:45:45,286 --> 00:45:49,992
In my ignorance, and the total stoppage
of my thoughts, I stood stock-still,

877
00:45:49,992 --> 00:45:54,901
and noticed various people crouching,
or shifting their positions.

878
00:45:54,901 --> 00:45:59,436
“Sit quiet,” said the dealer,
scornfully to the man near me.

879
00:45:59,436 --> 00:46:01,839
“Can’t you see he don’t
want to push trouble?

880
00:46:01,839 --> -1:59:59,000
He has handed Trampas the choice to back
down or draw his steel.

881
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

882
00:46:06,681 --> 00:46:13,355
Then, with equal suddenness and ease,
the room came out of its strangeness.

883
00:46:13,355 --> 00:46:17,356
Voices and cards, the click of chips,
the puff of tobacco,

884
00:46:17,356 --> 00:46:23,979
glasses lifted to drink⁠—this level of
smooth relaxation hinted no more plainly

885
00:46:23,979 --> 00:46:28,267
of what lay beneath than does the
surface tell the depth of the sea.

886
00:46:28,267 --> 00:46:30,290
For Trampas had made his choice.

887
00:46:30,290 --> 00:46:33,230
And that choice was not
to “draw his steel.”

888
00:46:33,230 --> 00:46:36,970
If it was knowledge that he sought,
he had found it, and no mistake!

889
00:46:36,970 --> 00:46:41,367
We heard no further reference to what he
had been pleased to style “amatures.”

890
00:46:41,367 --> 00:46:45,354
In no company would the black-headed man
who had visited Arizona be rated a

891
00:46:45,354 --> 00:46:47,867
novice at the cool art
of self-preservation.

892
00:46:47,867 --> 00:46:51,806
One doubt remained: what kind of
a man was Trampas?

893
00:46:51,806 --> 00:46:55,907
A public back-down is an unfinished
thing⁠—for some natures at least.

894
00:46:55,907 --> 00:46:58,508
I looked at his face,
and thought it sullen,

895
00:46:58,508 --> 00:47:00,998
but tricky rather than courageous.

896
00:47:00,998 --> 00:47:03,278
Something had been added
to my knowledge also.

897
00:47:03,278 --> 00:47:07,898
Once again I had heard applied to the
Virginian that epithet which

898
00:47:07,898 --> 00:47:09,700
Steve so freely used.

899
00:47:09,700 --> 00:47:12,812
The same words, identical to the letter.

900
00:47:12,812 --> 00:47:15,678
But this time they had produced a pistol.

901
00:47:15,678 --> 00:47:17,415
“When you call me that, smile!”

902
00:47:17,415 --> 00:47:21,109
So I perceived a new example of the old
truth, that the letter means nothing

903
00:47:21,109 --> 00:47:22,963
until the spirit gives it life.

904
00:47:22,963 --> 00:47:24,300
CHAPTER III

905
00:47:24,300 --> 00:47:25,864
Steve Treats

906
00:47:25,864 --> 00:47:29,693
It was for several minutes,
I suppose, that I stood

907
00:47:29,693 --> 00:47:32,798
drawing these silent morals.

908
00:47:32,798 --> 00:47:35,690
No man occupied himself with me.

909
00:47:35,690 --> 00:47:41,397
Quiet voices, and games of chance,
and glasses lifted to drink,

910
00:47:41,397 --> 00:47:44,070
continued to be the peaceful
order of the night.

911
00:47:44,070 --> 00:47:48,173
And into my thoughts broke the voice of
that card-dealer who had

912
00:47:48,173 --> 00:47:49,915
already spoken so sagely.

913
00:47:49,915 --> 00:47:52,877
He also took his turn at moralizing.

914
00:47:52,877 --> 00:47:53,923
“What did I tell you?”

915
00:47:53,923 --> 00:47:58,756
he remarked to the man for whom he
continued to deal, and who continued to

916
00:47:58,756 --> 00:47:59,945
lose money to him.

917
00:47:59,945 --> 00:48:00,922
“Tell me when?”

918
00:48:00,922 --> 00:48:03,442
“Didn’t I tell you he’d not shoot?”

919
00:48:03,442 --> 00:48:05,468
the dealer pursued with complacence.

920
00:48:05,468 --> 00:48:07,429
“You got ready to dodge.

921
00:48:07,429 --> 00:48:12,252
You had no call to be concerned.

922
00:48:12,252 --> 00:48:15,202
He’s not the kind a man
need feel anxious about.”

923
00:48:15,202 --> 00:48:18,212
The player looked over
at the Virginian, doubtfully.

924
00:48:18,212 --> 00:48:22,205
“Well,” he said, “I don’t know what you
folks call a dangerous man.”

925
00:48:22,205 --> 00:48:23,041
“Not him!”

926
00:48:23,041 --> 00:48:25,202
exclaimed the dealer with admiration.

927
00:48:25,202 --> 00:48:26,362
“He’s a brave man.

928
00:48:26,362 --> 00:48:27,429
That’s different.”

929
00:48:27,429 --> 00:48:30,813
The player seemed to follow this
reasoning no better than I did.

930
00:48:30,813 --> 00:48:34,584
“It’s not a brave man that’s
dangerous,” continued the dealer.

931
00:48:34,584 --> 00:48:36,559
“It’s the cowards that scare me.”

932
00:48:36,559 --> 00:48:39,433
He paused that this might sink home.

933
00:48:39,433 --> 00:48:41,754
“Fello’ came in here las’ Toosday

934
00:48:41,754 --> 00:48:42,666
,” he went on.

935
00:48:42,666 --> 00:48:46,128
“He got into some misunderstanding
about the drinks.

936
00:48:46,128 --> 00:48:52,868
Well, sir, before we could put him out of
business, he’d hurt two

937
00:48:52,868 --> 00:48:55,065
perfectly innocent onlookers.

938
00:48:55,065 --> 00:48:58,810
They’d no more to do with it than you
have,” the dealer explained to me.

939
00:48:58,810 --> 00:49:00,465
“Were they badly hurt?”

940
00:49:00,465 --> 00:49:01,665
I asked.

941
00:49:01,665 --> 00:49:02,649
“One of ’em was.

942
00:49:02,649 --> 00:49:04,214
He’s died since.”

943
00:49:04,214 --> 00:49:05,589
“What became of the man?”

944
00:49:05,589 --> 00:49:08,309
“Why, we put him out of
business, I told you.

945
00:49:08,309 --> 00:49:10,346
He died that night.

946
00:49:10,346 --> 00:49:14,217
But there was no occasion for any of it;
and that’s why I never like to be around

947
00:49:14,217 --> 00:49:15,292
where there’s a coward.

948
00:49:15,292 --> 00:49:16,384
You can’t tell.

949
00:49:16,384 --> 00:49:19,897
He’ll always go to shooting before it’s
necessary, and there’s no

950
00:49:19,897 --> 00:49:21,406
security who he’ll hit.

951
00:49:21,406 --> 00:49:26,691
But a man like that black-headed guy is
(the dealer indicated the Virginian)

952
00:49:26,691 --> 00:49:27,977
need never worry you.

953
00:49:27,977 --> 00:49:31,447
And there’s another point why there’s no
need to worry about him:

954
00:49:31,447 --> -1:59:59,000
it’ll be too late.

955
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

956
00:49:32,580 --> 00:49:36,270
These good words ended the
moralizing of the dealer.

957
00:49:36,270 --> 00:49:38,434
He had given us a piece of his mind.

958
00:49:38,434 --> 00:49:41,173
He now gave the whole of
it to dealing cards.

959
00:49:41,173 --> 00:49:45,428
I loitered here and there,
neither welcome nor unwelcome at

960
00:49:45,428 --> 00:49:48,585
present, watching the
cowboys at their play.

961
00:49:48,585 --> 00:49:53,314
Saving Trampas, there was scarce a face
among them that had not in

962
00:49:53,314 --> 00:49:55,037
it something very likable.

963
00:49:55,037 --> 00:49:59,314
Here were lusty horsemen ridden from the
heat of the sun, and the wet of the

964
00:49:59,314 --> 00:50:02,275
storm, to divert themselves awhile.

965
00:50:02,275 --> 00:50:07,111
Youth untamed sat here for an idle
moment, spending easily

966
00:50:07,111 --> 00:50:08,938
its hard-earned wages.

967
00:50:08,938 --> 00:50:14,215
City saloons rose into my vision,
and I instantly preferred

968
00:50:14,215 --> 00:50:16,580
this Rocky Mountain place.

969
00:50:16,580 --> 00:50:20,620
More of death it undoubtedly saw,
but less of vice, than did

970
00:50:20,620 --> -1:59:59,000
its New York equivalents

971
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
.

972
00:50:22,328 --> 00:50:25,272
And death is a thing much
cleaner than vice.

973
00:50:25,272 --> 00:50:29,655
Moreover, it was by no means vice that
was written upon these

974
00:50:29,655 --> 00:50:31,730
wild and manly faces.

975
00:50:31,730 --> 00:50:36,177
Even where baseness was visible,
baseness was not uppermost.

976
00:50:36,177 --> 00:50:42,311
Daring, laughter, endurance⁠—these were
what I saw upon the countenances

977
00:50:42,311 --> 00:50:43,609
of the cowboys.

978
00:50:43,609 --> 00:50:48,686
And this very first day of my knowledge
of them marks a date with me.

979
00:50:48,686 --> 00:50:51,920
For something about them,
and the idea of them,

980
00:50:51,920 --> 00:50:56,037
smote my American heart,
and I have never forgotten it,

981
00:50:56,037 --> 00:50:58,955
nor ever shall, as long as I live.

982
00:50:58,955 --> 00:51:04,713
In their flesh our natural passions ran
tumultuous; but often in their spirit

983
00:51:04,713 --> 00:51:09,985
sat hidden a true nobility,
and often beneath its unexpected shining

984
00:51:09,985 --> 00:51:13,181
their figures took on heroic stature.

985
00:51:13,181 --> 00:51:17,827
The dealer had styled the Virginian
“a black-headed guy.”

986
00:51:17,827 --> 00:51:20,796
This did well enough as
an unflattered portrait.

987
00:51:20,796 --> 00:51:26,508
Judge Henry’s trustworthy man,
with whom I was to drive two hundred and

988
00:51:26,508 --> 00:51:30,560
sixty-three miles, certainly had a very
black head of hair.

989
00:51:30,560 --> 00:51:35,119
It was the first thing to notice now,
if one glanced generally at the table

990
00:51:35,119 --> 00:51:36,682
where he sat at cards.

991
00:51:36,682 --> 00:51:40,953
But the eye came back to him⁠—drawn by
that inexpressible something which had

992
00:51:40,953 --> 00:51:43,810
led the dealer to speak so much
at length about him.

993
00:51:43,810 --> 00:51:50,027
Still, “black-headed guy” justly fits him
and his next performance.

994
00:51:50,027 --> 00:51:54,508
He had made his plan for this like a true
and (I must say) inspired devil.

995
00:51:54,508 --> 00:51:58,348
And now the highly appreciative town of
Medicine Bow was to be treated to

996
00:51:58,348 --> 00:52:01,039
a manifestation of genius.

997
00:52:01,039 --> 00:52:02,959
He sat playing his stud-poker.

998
00:52:02,959 --> 00:52:07,199
After a decent period of losing and
winning, which gave Trampas all proper

999
00:52:07,199 --> 00:52:11,428
time for a change of luck and a
repairing of his fortunes,

1000
00:52:11,428 --> 00:52:13,623
he looked at Steve and said amiably:⁠—

1001
00:52:13,623 --> 00:52:16,136
“How does bed strike you?”

1002
00:52:16,136 --> 00:52:20,777
I was beside their table,
learning gradually that stud-poker has

1003
00:52:20,777 --> 00:52:25,942
in it more of what I will call red
pepper than has our Eastern game.

1004
00:52:25,942 --> 00:52:28,178
The Virginian followed his own question:⁠—

1005
00:52:28,178 --> 00:52:30,445
“Bed strikes me,” he stated.

1006
00:52:30,445 --> 00:52:32,989
Steve feigned indifference.

1007
00:52:32,989 --> 00:52:37,445
He was far more deeply absorbed in his
bet and the American drummer than he was

1008
00:52:37,445 --> 00:52:42,020
in this game; but he chose to take out a
fat, florid gold watch,

1009
00:52:42,020 --> 00:52:46,289
consult it elaborately,
and remark, “It’s only eleven.”

1010
00:52:46,289 --> 00:52:52,672
“Yu’ forget I’m from the country,”
said the black-headed guy.

1011
00:52:52,672 --> 00:52:55,244
“The chickens have been roostin’
a right smart while.”

1012
00:52:55,244 --> 00:52:57,952
His sunny Southern accent
was again strong.

1013
00:52:57,952 --> 00:53:04,603
In that brief passage with Trampas it had
been almost wholly absent.

1014
00:53:04,603 --> 00:53:10,324
But different moods of the spirit bring
different qualities of utterance⁠—where

1015
00:53:10,324 --> 00:53:12,564
a man comes by these naturally.

1016
00:53:12,564 --> 00:53:15,323
The Virginian cashed in his checks.

1017
00:53:15,323 --> 00:53:19,667
“Awhile ago,” said Steve,
“you had won three months’ salary.”

1018
00:53:19,667 --> 00:53:22,857
“I’m still twenty dollars to the
good,” said the Virginian.

1019
00:53:22,857 --> 00:53:24,868
“That’s better than breaking a laig.”

1020
00:53:24,868 --> 00:53:30,169
Again, in some voiceless,
masonic way, most people in that saloon

1021
00:53:30,169 --> 00:53:34,209
had become aware that something was
in process of happening.

1022
00:53:34,209 --> 00:53:40,126
Several left their games and came to the
front by the bar.

1023
00:53:40,126 --> 00:53:42,859
“If he ain’t in bed yet⁠—”
mused the Virginian.

1024
00:53:42,859 --> 00:53:45,510
“I’ll find out,” said I.

1025
00:53:45,510 --> 00:53:49,884
And I hurried across to the dim sleeping
room, happy to have a part in this.

1026
00:53:49,884 --> 00:53:53,905
They were all in bed;
and in some beds two were sleeping.

1027
00:53:53,905 --> 00:53:59,733
How they could do it⁠—but in those
days I was fastidious.

1028
00:53:59,733 --> 00:54:03,399
The American had come in recently
and was still awake.

1029
00:54:03,399 --> 00:54:06,472
“Thought you were to sleep at the store?”

1030
00:54:06,472 --> 00:54:07,567
said he.

1031
00:54:07,567 --> 00:54:10,794
So then I invented a little lie,
and explained that I was in

1032
00:54:10,794 --> 00:54:12,194
search of the Virginian.

1033
00:54:12,194 --> 00:54:15,148
“Better search the dives,” said he.

1034
00:54:15,148 --> 00:54:17,498
“These cowboys don’t get to town often.”

1035
00:54:17,498 --> 00:54:20,789
At this point I stumbled
sharply over something.

1036
00:54:20,789 --> 00:54:23,852
“It’s my box of Consumption Killer,”
explained the drummer;

1037
00:54:23,852 --> 00:54:27,102
“Well, I hope that man will
stay out all night.”

1038
00:54:27,102 --> 00:54:28,845
“Bed narrow?”

1039
00:54:28,845 --> 00:54:29,665
I inquired.

1040
00:54:29,665 --> 00:54:31,776
“For two it is.

1041
00:54:31,776 --> 00:54:33,883
And the pillows are mean.

1042
00:54:33,883 --> 00:54:37,080
Takes both before you feel
anything’s under your head.”

1043
00:54:37,080 --> 00:54:40,327
He yawned, and I wished
him pleasant dreams.

1044
00:54:40,327 --> 00:54:45,786
At my news the Virginian left the bar at
once; and crossed to the sleeping room.

1045
00:54:45,786 --> 00:54:51,032
Steve and I followed softly,
and behind us several more strung out

1046
00:54:51,032 --> 00:54:52,752
in an expectant line.

1047
00:54:52,752 --> 00:54:54,394
“What is this going to be?”

1048
00:54:54,394 --> 00:54:57,188
they inquired curiously of each other.

1049
00:54:57,188 --> 00:55:02,026
And upon learning the great novelty of
the event, they clustered with silence

1050
00:55:02,026 --> 00:55:05,775
intense outside the door where the
Virginian had gone in.

1051
00:55:05,775 --> 00:55:10,310
We heard the voice of the
drummer, cautioning his bedfellow.

1052
00:55:10,310 --> 00:55:13,310
“Don’t trip over the Killer,”
he was saying.

1053
00:55:13,310 --> 00:55:16,906
“The Prince of Wales barked
his shin just now.”

1054
00:55:16,906 --> 00:55:20,178
It seemed my English clothes had
earned me this title.

1055
00:55:20,178 --> 00:55:23,258
The boots of the Virginian were
next heard to drop.

1056
00:55:23,258 --> 00:55:24,721
“Can yu’ make out what he’s at?”

1057
00:55:24,721 --> 00:55:25,632
whispered Steve.

1058
00:55:25,632 --> 00:55:27,127
He was plainly undressing.

1059
00:55:27,127 --> 00:55:31,454
The rip of swift unbuttoning told us that
the black-headed guy must now

1060
00:55:31,454 --> 00:55:33,253
be removing his overalls.

1061
00:55:33,253 --> 00:55:35,895
“Why, thank yu’, no,”
he was replying to a

1062
00:55:35,895 --> 00:55:37,175
question of the drummer.

1063
00:55:37,175 --> 00:55:39,356
“Outside or in’s all one to me.”

1064
00:55:39,356 --> 00:55:43,368
“Then, if you’d just as
soon take the wall⁠—”

1065
00:55:43,368 --> 00:55:45,597
“Why, cert’nly.”

1066
00:55:45,597 --> 00:55:52,682
There was a sound of bedclothes,
and creaking.

1067
00:55:52,682 --> 00:55:56,813
“This hyeh pillo’ needs a Southern
climate,” was the Virginian’s

1068
00:55:56,813 --> 00:55:58,134
next observation.

1069
00:55:58,134 --> 00:56:01,577
Many listeners had now
gathered at the door.

1070
00:56:01,577 --> 00:56:04,124
The dealer and the player were both here.

1071
00:56:04,124 --> 00:56:08,004
The storekeeper was present,
and I recognized the agent of the Union

1072
00:56:08,004 --> 00:56:10,044
Pacific Railroad among the crowd.

1073
00:56:10,044 --> 00:56:14,548
We made a large company,
and I felt that trembling sensation

1074
00:56:14,548 --> 00:56:19,819
which is common when the cap of a camera
is about to be removed upon a group.

1075
00:56:19,819 --> 00:56:24,289
“I should think,” said the drummer’s
voice, “that you’d feel your knife and

1076
00:56:24,289 --> 00:56:26,169
gun clean through that pillow.”

1077
00:56:26,169 --> 00:56:28,462
“I do,” responded the Virginian.

1078
00:56:28,462 --> 00:56:31,582
“I should think you’d put them on a
chair and be comfortable.”

1079
00:56:31,582 --> -1:59:59,000
“I’d be uncomfortable, then.

1080
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1081
00:56:33,002 --> 00:56:35,212
“Used to the feel of them, I suppose?”

1082
00:56:35,212 --> 00:56:35,984
“That’s it.

1083
00:56:35,984 --> 00:56:37,561
Used to the feel of them.

1084
00:56:37,561 --> 00:56:40,593
I would miss them, and that
would make me wakeful.”

1085
00:56:40,593 --> 00:56:42,072
“Well, good night.”

1086
00:56:42,072 --> 00:56:42,992
“Good night.

1087
00:56:42,992 --> 00:56:48,361
If I get to talkin’ and tossin’, or
whatnot, you’ll understand you’re to⁠—”

1088
00:56:48,361 --> -1:59:59,000
“Yes, I’ll wake you.

1089
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1090
00:56:50,197 --> -1:59:59,000
“No, don’t yu’, for God’s sake!

1091
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1092
00:56:53,170 --> 00:56:53,954
“Not?”

1093
00:56:53,954 --> 00:56:55,926
“Don’t yu’ touch me.”

1094
00:56:55,926 --> 00:56:57,577
“What’ll I do?”

1095
00:56:57,577 --> 00:56:59,417
“Roll away quick to your side.

1096
00:56:59,417 --> 00:57:01,224
It don’t last but a minute.”

1097
00:57:01,224 --> 00:57:04,354
The Virginian spoke with
a reassuring drawl.

1098
00:57:04,354 --> 00:57:09,050
Upon this there fell a brief silence,
and I heard the drummer clear his

1099
00:57:09,050 --> 00:57:10,921
throat once or twice.

1100
00:57:10,921 --> 00:57:13,003
“It’s merely the nightmare, I suppose?”

1101
00:57:13,003 --> 00:57:15,785
he said after a throat clearing.

1102
00:57:15,785 --> 00:57:17,326
“Lord, yes.

1103
00:57:17,326 --> 00:57:20,977
That’s all.

1104
00:57:20,977 --> 00:57:25,506
And don’t happen twice a year.

1105
00:57:25,506 --> 00:57:27,511
Was you thinkin’ it was fits?”

1106
00:57:27,511 --> 00:57:28,276
“Oh, no!

1107
00:57:28,276 --> 00:57:29,545
I just wanted to know.

1108
00:57:29,545 --> 00:57:33,682
I’ve been told before that it was not
safe for a person to be waked suddenly

1109
00:57:33,682 --> 00:57:35,357
that way out of a nightmare.”

1110
00:57:35,357 --> 00:57:37,288
“Yes, I have heard that too.

1111
00:57:37,288 --> 00:57:39,775
But it never harms me any.

1112
00:57:39,775 --> 00:57:41,783
I didn’t want you to run risks.”

1113
00:57:41,783 --> 00:57:43,145
“Me?”

1114
00:57:43,145 --> 00:57:46,336
“Oh, it’ll be all right now that yu’
know how it is.”

1115
00:57:46,336 --> 00:57:49,096
The Virginian’s drawl
was full of assurance.

1116
00:57:49,096 --> 00:57:51,999
There was a second pause,
after which the drummer said:⁠—

1117
00:57:51,999 --> 00:57:53,856
“Tell me again how it is.”

1118
00:57:53,856 --> 00:57:58,650
The Virginian answered very drowsily:
“Oh, just don’t let your arm or your

1119
00:57:58,650 --> 00:58:01,050
laig touch me if I go to jumpin’ around.

1120
00:58:01,050 --> 00:58:04,088
I’m dreamin’ of Indians when I do that.

1121
00:58:04,088 --> 00:58:07,313
And if anything touches me then,
I’m liable to grab my knife

1122
00:58:07,313 --> 00:58:08,287
right in my sleep.”

1123
00:58:08,287 --> 00:58:11,883
“Oh, I understand,” said the
drummer, clearing his throat.

1124
00:58:11,883 --> 00:58:13,528
“Yes.”

1125
00:58:13,528 --> 00:58:19,281
Steve was whispering delighted oaths to
himself, and in his joy applying to the

1126
00:58:19,281 --> 00:58:22,334
Virginian one unprintable
name after another.

1127
00:58:22,334 --> 00:58:26,487
We listened again, but now
no further words came.

1128
00:58:26,487 --> 00:58:30,509
Listening very hard, I could half make
out the progress of a heavy breathing,

1129
00:58:30,509 --> 00:58:32,903
and a restless turning
I could clearly detect.

1130
00:58:32,903 --> 00:58:34,874
This was the wretched drummer.

1131
00:58:34,874 --> 00:58:36,245
He was waiting.

1132
00:58:36,245 --> 00:58:37,768
But he did not wait long.

1133
00:58:37,768 --> 00:58:41,925
Again there was a light creak,
and after it a light step.

1134
00:58:41,925 --> 00:58:45,943
He was not even going to put his boots on
in the fatal neighborhood of the

1135
00:58:45,943 --> 00:58:46,653
dreamer.

1136
00:58:46,653 --> 00:58:51,523
By a happy thought Medicine Bow formed
into two lines, making an

1137
00:58:51,523 --> 00:58:53,014
avenue from the door.

1138
00:58:53,014 --> 00:58:57,219
And then the commercial traveller
forgot his Consumption Killer.

1139
00:58:57,219 --> 00:58:58,884
He fell heavily over it.

1140
00:58:58,884 --> 00:59:03,257
Immediately from the bed the Virginian
gave forth a dreadful howl.

1141
00:59:03,257 --> 00:59:07,718
And then everything happened at once;
and how shall mere words narrate it?

1142
00:59:07,718 --> 00:59:12,639
The door burst open, and out flew the
commercial traveller in his stockings.

1143
00:59:12,639 --> 00:59:17,918
One hand held a lump of coat and trousers
with suspenders dangling,

1144
00:59:17,918 --> 00:59:19,857
his boots were clutched in the other.

1145
00:59:19,857 --> 00:59:22,644
The sight of us stopped his flight short.

1146
00:59:22,644 --> 00:59:27,467
He gazed, the boots fell from his hand;
and at his profane explosion,

1147
00:59:27,467 --> 00:59:33,634
Medicine Bow set up a united,
unearthly noise and began to play

1148
00:59:33,634 --> 00:59:35,274
Virginia reel with him.

1149
00:59:35,274 --> 00:59:39,044
The other occupants of the beds had
already sprung out of them,

1150
00:59:39,044 --> 00:59:42,933
clothed chiefly with their pistols,
and ready for war.

1151
00:59:42,933 --> 00:59:43,846
“What is it?”

1152
00:59:43,846 --> 00:59:44,994
they demanded.

1153
00:59:44,994 --> 00:59:46,344
“What is it?”

1154
00:59:46,344 --> 00:59:52,000
“Why, I reckon it’s drinks on Steve,”
said the Virginian from his bed.

1155
00:59:52,000 --> 00:59:57,819
And he gave the first broad grin that I
had seen from him.

1156
00:59:57,819 --> 00:59:59,456
“I’ll set ’em up all night!”

1157
00:59:59,456 --> 01:00:02,870
Steve shouted, as the
reel went on regardless.

1158
01:00:02,870 --> 01:00:07,165
The drummer was bawling to be allowed to
put at least his boots on.

1159
01:00:07,165 --> 01:00:12,239
“This way, Pard,” was the answer;
and another man whirled him round.

1160
01:00:12,239 --> 01:00:13,409
“This way, Beau!”

1161
01:00:13,409 --> 01:00:15,008
they called to him; “This way, Budd!”

1162
01:00:15,008 --> 01:00:17,811
and he was passed like a
shuttlecock down the line.

1163
01:00:17,811 --> 01:00:22,070
Suddenly the leaders bounded
into the sleeping-room.

1164
01:00:22,070 --> 01:00:23,293
“Feed the machine!”

1165
01:00:23,293 --> 01:00:23,944
they said.

1166
01:00:23,944 --> 01:00:24,900
“Feed her!”

1167
01:00:24,900 --> 01:00:29,336
And seizing the German drummer who sold
jewellery, they flung him into the

1168
01:00:29,336 --> 01:00:30,577
trough of the reel.

1169
01:00:30,577 --> 01:00:33,894
I saw him go bouncing like an ear of corn
to be shelled, and the

1170
01:00:33,894 --> 01:00:35,071
dance ingulfed him.

1171
01:00:35,071 --> 01:00:39,816
I saw a Jew sent rattling after him;
and next they threw in the railroad

1172
01:00:39,816 --> 01:00:43,933
employee, and the other Jew;
and while I stood mesmerized,

1173
01:00:43,933 --> 01:00:45,682
my own feet left the earth.

1174
01:00:45,682 --> 01:00:50,048
I shot from the room and sped like a
bobbing cork into this mill race,

1175
01:00:50,048 --> 01:00:53,439
whirling my turn in the wake of the
others amid cries of,

1176
01:00:53,439 --> 01:00:55,429
“Here comes the Prince of Wales!”

1177
01:00:55,429 --> 01:00:58,116
There was soon not much English
left about my raiment.

1178
01:00:58,116 --> 01:01:00,328
They were now shouting for music.

1179
01:01:00,328 --> 01:01:06,014
Medicine Bow swept in like a cloud of
dust to where a fiddler sat playing in a

1180
01:01:06,014 --> 01:01:10,086
hall; and gathering up fiddler and
dancers, swept out again,

1181
01:01:10,086 --> 01:01:12,830
a larger Medicine Bow,
growing all the while.

1182
01:01:12,830 --> 01:01:16,319
Steve offered us the freedom
of the house, everywhere.

1183
01:01:16,319 --> 01:01:20,629
He implored us to call for whatever
pleased us, and as many times

1184
01:01:20,629 --> 01:01:22,091
as we should please.

1185
01:01:22,091 --> 01:01:26,771
He ordered the town to be searched for
more citizens to come and help

1186
01:01:26,771 --> 01:01:28,066
him pay his bet.

1187
01:01:28,066 --> 01:01:31,014
But changing his mind,
kegs and bottles were now

1188
01:01:31,014 --> 01:01:32,590
carried along with us.

1189
01:01:32,590 --> 01:01:37,017
We had found three fiddlers,
and these played busily for us;

1190
01:01:37,017 --> 01:01:42,135
and thus we set out to visit all cabins
and houses where people might still by

1191
01:01:42,135 --> 01:01:44,015
some miracle be asleep.

1192
01:01:44,015 --> 01:01:47,100
The first man put out his head to decline.

1193
01:01:47,100 --> 01:01:51,596
But such a possibility had been foreseen
by the proprietor of the store.

1194
01:01:51,596 --> 01:01:55,591
This seemingly respectable man now came
dragging some sort of apparatus from his

1195
01:01:55,591 --> 01:01:57,568
place, helped by the Virginian.

1196
01:01:57,568 --> 01:02:00,880
The cowboys cheered, for they
knew what this was.

1197
01:02:00,880 --> 01:02:05,264
The man in his window likewise recognized
it, and uttering a groan,

1198
01:02:05,264 --> 01:02:07,577
came immediately out and joined us.

1199
01:02:07,577 --> 01:02:11,475
What it was, I also learned
in a few minutes.

1200
01:02:11,475 --> 01:02:15,456
For we found a house where the people
made no sign at either our

1201
01:02:15,456 --> 01:02:17,674
fiddlers or our knocking.

1202
01:02:17,674 --> 01:02:20,766
And then the infernal machine
was set to work.

1203
01:02:20,766 --> 01:02:24,717
Its parts seemed to be no more than an
empty keg and a plank.

1204
01:02:24,717 --> 01:02:28,879
Some citizen informed me that I should
soon have a new idea of noise;

1205
01:02:28,879 --> 01:02:32,367
and I nerved myself for something severe
in the way of gunpowder.

1206
01:02:32,367 --> 01:02:36,280
But the Virginian and the proprietor now
sat on the ground holding the keg

1207
01:02:36,280 --> 01:02:40,721
braced, and two others got down
apparently to play seesaw over the top

1208
01:02:40,721 --> 01:02:42,254
of it with the plank.

1209
01:02:42,254 --> 01:02:47,451
But the keg and plank had been rubbed
with rosin, and they drew the plank back

1210
01:02:47,451 --> 01:02:49,892
and forth over the keg.

1211
01:02:49,892 --> 01:02:54,962
Do you know the sound made in a narrow
street by a dray loaded

1212
01:02:54,962 --> 01:02:56,309
with strips of iron?

1213
01:02:56,309 --> 01:03:03,129
That noise is a lullaby compared with the
staggering, blinding bellow which

1214
01:03:03,129 --> 01:03:04,777
rose from the keg.

1215
01:03:04,777 --> 01:03:09,032
If you were to try it in your native
town, you would not merely be arrested,

1216
01:03:09,032 --> 01:03:11,796
you would be hanged,
and everybody would be glad,

1217
01:03:11,796 --> 01:03:13,870
and the clergyman would not bury you.

1218
01:03:13,870 --> 01:03:20,191
My head, my teeth, the whole system of my
bones leaped and chattered at the din,

1219
01:03:20,191 --> 01:03:25,921
and out of the house like drops squirted
from a lemon came a man and his wife.

1220
01:03:25,921 --> 01:03:29,415
No time was given them.

1221
01:03:29,415 --> 01:03:34,867
They were swept along with the rest;
and having been routed from their own

1222
01:03:34,867 --> 01:03:38,107
bed, they now became most furious in
assailing the remaining

1223
01:03:38,107 --> 01:03:40,147
homes of Medicine Bow.

1224
01:03:40,147 --> 01:03:41,988
Everybody was to come out.

1225
01:03:41,988 --> 01:03:46,201
Many were now riding horses at top speed
out into the plains and back,

1226
01:03:46,201 --> 01:03:49,387
while the procession of the plank and
keg continued its work,

1227
01:03:49,387 --> 01:03:52,205
and the fiddlers played incessantly.

1228
01:03:52,205 --> 01:03:54,236
Suddenly there was a quiet.

1229
01:03:54,236 --> 01:03:58,780
I did not see who brought the message;
but the word ran among us that there was

1230
01:03:58,780 --> 01:04:03,912
a woman⁠—the engineer’s woman down by
the water-tank⁠—very sick.

1231
01:04:03,912 --> 01:04:06,712
The doctor had been to
see her from Laramie.

1232
01:04:06,712 --> 01:04:08,646
Everybody liked the engineer.

1233
01:04:08,646 --> 01:04:12,332
Plank and keg were heard no more.

1234
01:04:12,332 --> 01:04:16,125
The horsemen found it out
and restrained their gambols.

1235
01:04:16,125 --> 01:04:19,353
Medicine Bow went gradually home.

1236
01:04:19,353 --> 01:04:23,525
I saw doors shutting,
and lights go out; I saw a late few

1237
01:04:23,525 --> 01:04:27,209
reassemble at the card tables,
and the drummers gathered themselves

1238
01:04:27,209 --> 01:04:31,406
together for sleep; the proprietor of
the store (you could not see a more

1239
01:04:31,406 --> 01:04:35,977
respectable-looking person) hoped that I
would be comfortable on the quilts;

1240
01:04:35,977 --> 01:04:40,931
and I heard Steve urging the Virginian
to take one more glass.

1241
01:04:40,931 --> 01:04:44,092
“We’ve not met for so long,” he said.

1242
01:04:44,092 --> 01:04:49,371
But the Virginian, the black-headed guy
who had set all this nonsense going,

1243
01:04:49,371 --> 01:04:50,733
said No to Steve.

1244
01:04:50,733 --> 01:04:57,315
“I have got to stay responsible,”
was his excuse to his friend.

1245
01:04:57,315 --> 01:05:01,065
And the friend looked at me.

1246
01:05:01,065 --> 01:05:07,545
Therefore I surmised that the Judge’s
trustworthy man found me an

1247
01:05:07,545 --> 01:05:10,454
embarrassment to his holiday.

1248
01:05:10,454 --> 01:05:13,309
But if he did, he never showed it to me.

1249
01:05:13,309 --> 01:05:19,713
He had been sent to meet a stranger and
drive him to Sunk Creek in safety,

1250
01:05:19,713 --> 01:05:23,083
and this charge he would allow
no temptation to imperil.

1251
01:05:23,083 --> 01:05:25,100
He nodded good night to me.

1252
01:05:25,100 --> 01:05:27,837
“If there’s anything I can do for
yu’, you’ll tell me.”

1253
01:05:27,837 --> 01:05:29,201
I thanked him.

1254
01:05:29,201 --> 01:05:31,423
“What a pleasant evening!”

1255
01:05:31,423 --> 01:05:32,143
I added.

1256
01:05:32,143 --> -1:59:59,000
“I’m glad yu’ found it so.

1257
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1258
01:05:34,811 --> 01:05:38,078
Again his manner put a
bar to my approaches.

1259
01:05:38,078 --> 01:05:42,208
Even though I had seen him wildly
disporting himself, those were matters

1260
01:05:42,208 --> 01:05:44,406
which he chose not to discuss with me.

1261
01:05:44,406 --> 01:05:49,076
Medicine Bow was quiet as I went my
way to my quilts.

1262
01:05:49,076 --> 01:05:55,793
So still, that through the air the deep
whistles of the freight trains came from

1263
01:05:55,793 --> 01:06:00,758
below the horizon across
great miles of silence.

1264
01:06:00,758 --> 01:06:05,128
I passed cowboys, whom half an hour
before I had seen prancing and roaring,

1265
01:06:05,128 --> 01:06:10,136
now rolled in their blankets beneath the
open and shining night.

1266
01:06:10,136 --> 01:06:11,256
“What world am I in?”

1267
01:06:11,256 --> 01:06:12,424
I said aloud.

1268
01:06:12,424 --> 01:06:14,696
“Does this same planet hold Fifth Avenue?”

1269
01:06:14,696 --> 01:06:17,960
And I went to sleep, pondering
over my native land.

1270
01:06:17,960 --> 01:06:18,890
CHAPTER IV

1271
01:06:18,890 --> 01:06:20,749
Deep Into Cattle Land

1272
01:06:20,749 --> 01:06:26,579
Morning had been for some while astir in
Medicine Bow before I left my quilts.

1273
01:06:26,579 --> 01:06:31,311
The new day and its doings began around
me in the store, chiefly

1274
01:06:31,311 --> 01:06:32,892
at the grocery counter.

1275
01:06:32,892 --> 01:06:35,801
Dry-goods were not in great request.

1276
01:06:35,801 --> 01:06:40,484
The early rising cowboys were off again
to their work; and those to whom their

1277
01:06:40,484 --> 01:06:45,695
night’s holiday had left any dollars
were spending these for tobacco,

1278
01:06:45,695 --> 01:06:50,300
or cartridges, or canned provisions for
the journey to their distant camps.

1279
01:06:50,300 --> 01:06:55,328
Sardines were called for,
and potted chicken, and devilled ham:

1280
01:06:55,328 --> 01:06:59,039
a sophisticated nourishment,
at first sight, for these

1281
01:06:59,039 --> 01:07:01,259
sons of the sagebrush.

1282
01:07:01,259 --> 01:07:06,060
But portable ready-made food plays of
necessity a great part in the opening

1283
01:07:06,060 --> 01:07:07,105
of a new country.

1284
01:07:07,105 --> 01:07:12,222
These picnic pots and cans were the first
of her trophies that Civilization

1285
01:07:12,222 --> 01:07:16,584
dropped upon Wyoming’s virgin soil.

1286
01:07:16,584 --> 01:07:20,160
The cowboy is now gone to worlds
invisible; the wind has blown away the

1287
01:07:20,160 --> 01:07:24,250
white ashes of his campfires;
but the empty sardine box lies rusting

1288
01:07:24,250 --> 01:07:26,801
over the face of the Western earth.

1289
01:07:26,801 --> 01:07:32,176
So through my eyes half closed I watched
the sale of these tins,

1290
01:07:32,176 --> 01:07:36,016
and grew familiar with the ham’s
inevitable trademark⁠—that label with

1291
01:07:36,016 --> 01:07:40,681
the devil and his horns and hoofs and
tail very pronounced,

1292
01:07:40,681 --> 01:07:46,297
all colored a sultry prodigious scarlet.

1293
01:07:46,297 --> 01:07:51,462
And when each horseman had made his
purchase, he would trail his spurs over

1294
01:07:51,462 --> 01:07:56,348
the floor, and presently the sound of
his horse’s hoofs would be

1295
01:07:56,348 --> 01:07:57,423
the last of him.

1296
01:07:57,423 --> 01:08:02,428
Through my dozing attention came various
fragments of talk, and sometimes

1297
01:08:02,428 --> 01:08:04,367
useful bits of knowledge.

1298
01:08:04,367 --> 01:08:10,932
For instance, I learned the true value of
tomatoes in this country.

1299
01:08:10,932 --> 01:08:13,338
One fellow was buying two cans of them.

1300
01:08:13,338 --> 01:08:15,255
“Meadow Creek dry already?”

1301
01:08:15,255 --> 01:08:17,298
commented the proprietor.

1302
01:08:17,298 --> 01:08:21,496
“Been dry ten days,” the
young cowboy informed him.

1303
01:08:21,496 --> 01:08:26,366
And it appeared that along the road he
was going, water would not be reached

1304
01:08:26,366 --> 01:08:29,854
much before sundown,
because this Meadow Creek

1305
01:08:29,854 --> 01:08:31,242
had ceased to run.

1306
01:08:31,242 --> 01:08:33,445
His tomatoes were for drink.

1307
01:08:33,445 --> 01:08:38,632
And thus they have refreshed
me many times since.

1308
01:08:38,632 --> 01:08:39,632
“No beer?”

1309
01:08:39,632 --> 01:08:41,257
suggested the proprietor.

1310
01:08:41,257 --> 01:08:43,171
The boy made a shuddering face.

1311
01:08:43,171 --> 01:08:45,346
“Don’t say its name to me!”

1312
01:08:45,346 --> 01:08:46,634
he exclaimed.

1313
01:08:46,634 --> 01:08:49,019
“I couldn’t hold my breakfast down.”

1314
01:08:49,019 --> 01:08:51,793
He rang his silver money upon the counter.

1315
01:08:51,793 --> 01:08:55,073
“I’ve swore off for three
months,” he stated.

1316
01:08:55,073 --> 01:08:57,116
“I’m going to be as pure as the snow!”

1317
01:08:57,116 --> 01:09:01,840
And away he went jingling out of the
door, to ride seventy-five miles.

1318
01:09:01,840 --> 01:09:05,821
Three more months of hard,
unsheltered work, and he would ride into

1319
01:09:05,821 --> 01:09:09,866
town again, with his adolescent blood
crying aloud for its own.

1320
01:09:09,866 --> 01:09:14,503
“I’m obliged,” said a new voice,
rousing me from a new doze.

1321
01:09:14,503 --> 01:09:17,015
“She’s easier this morning,
since the medicine.”

1322
01:09:17,015 --> 01:09:20,728
This was the engineer,
whose sick wife had brought a hush

1323
01:09:20,728 --> 01:09:22,745
over Medicine Bow’s rioting.

1324
01:09:22,745 --> 01:09:27,293
“I’ll give her them flowers soon as
she wakes,” he added.

1325
01:09:27,293 --> 01:09:28,968
“Flowers?”

1326
01:09:28,968 --> 01:09:31,168
repeated the proprietor.

1327
01:09:31,168 --> 01:09:33,529
“You didn’t leave that bunch at our door?”

1328
01:09:33,529 --> 01:09:35,350
“Wish I’d thought to do it.”

1329
01:09:35,350 --> 01:09:38,274
“She likes to see flowers,”
said the engineer.

1330
01:09:38,274 --> 01:09:42,058
And he walked out slowly,
with his thanks unachieved.

1331
01:09:42,058 --> 01:09:47,579
He returned at once with the Virginian;
for in the band of the Virginian’s hat

1332
01:09:47,579 --> 01:09:50,446
were two or three blossoms.

1333
01:09:50,446 --> 01:09:54,181
“It don’t need mentioning,”
the Southerner was saying,

1334
01:09:54,181 --> 01:09:57,186
embarrassed by any expression of thanks.

1335
01:09:57,186 --> 01:09:58,741
“If we had knowed last night⁠—”

1336
01:09:58,741 --> 01:10:01,570
“You didn’t disturb her any,”
broke in the engineer.

1337
01:10:01,570 --> 01:10:04,140
“She’s easier this morning.

1338
01:10:04,140 --> 01:10:06,601
I’ll tell her about them flowers.”

1339
01:10:06,601 --> 01:10:10,842
“Why, it don’t need mentioning,”
the Virginian again protested,

1340
01:10:10,842 --> 01:10:11,782
almost crossly.

1341
01:10:11,782 --> 01:10:15,543
“The little things looked kind o’ fresh,
and I just picked them.”

1342
01:10:15,543 --> 01:10:19,742
His eye now fell upon me,
where I lay upon the counter.

1343
01:10:19,742 --> 01:10:23,451
“I reckon breakfast will be
getting through,” he remarked.

1344
01:10:23,451 --> 01:10:25,422
I was soon at the wash trough.

1345
01:10:25,422 --> 01:10:29,812
It was only half-past six,
but many had been before me⁠—one glance

1346
01:10:29,812 --> 01:10:31,558
at the roller-towel told me that.

1347
01:10:31,558 --> 01:10:35,172
I was afraid to ask the landlady for a
clean one, and so I found a fresh

1348
01:10:35,172 --> 01:10:37,795
handkerchief, and accomplished
a sparing toilet.

1349
01:10:37,795 --> 01:10:43,726
In the midst of this the drummers joined
me, one by one, and they used the

1350
01:10:43,726 --> 01:10:46,571
degraded towel without hesitation.

1351
01:10:46,571 --> 01:10:50,000
In a way they had the best of me;
filth was nothing to them.

1352
01:10:50,000 --> 01:10:53,806
The latest risers in Medicine Bow,
we sat at breakfast together;

1353
01:10:53,806 --> 01:10:57,086
and they essayed some light
familiarities with the landlady.

1354
01:10:57,086 --> 01:11:00,147
But these experiments were failures.

1355
01:11:00,147 --> 01:11:03,919
Her eyes did not see,
nor did her ears hear them.

1356
01:11:03,919 --> 01:11:09,335
She brought the coffee and the bacon with
a sedateness that propriety itself

1357
01:11:09,335 --> 01:11:11,601
could scarce have surpassed.

1358
01:11:11,601 --> 01:11:17,295
Yet impropriety lurked
noiselessly all over her.

1359
01:11:17,295 --> 01:11:22,193
You could not have specified how;
it was interblended with her sum total.

1360
01:11:22,193 --> 01:11:28,779
Silence was her apparent habit and her
weapon; but the American drummer found

1361
01:11:28,779 --> 01:11:32,939
that she could speak to the point when
need came for this.

1362
01:11:32,939 --> 01:11:36,918
During the meal he had
praised her golden hair.

1363
01:11:36,918 --> 01:11:40,730
It was golden indeed,
and worth a high compliment;

1364
01:11:40,730 --> 01:11:43,562
but his kind displeased her.

1365
01:11:43,562 --> 01:11:47,337
She had let it pass, however,
with no more than a cool stare.

1366
01:11:47,337 --> 01:11:51,159
But on taking his leave,
when he came to pay for the meal,

1367
01:11:51,159 --> 01:11:52,688
he pushed it too far.

1368
01:11:52,688 --> 01:11:56,097
“Pity this must be our last,”
he said; and as it brought

1369
01:11:56,097 --> 01:11:58,505
no answer, “Ever travel?”

1370
01:11:58,505 --> 01:11:59,350
he inquired.

1371
01:11:59,350 --> -1:59:59,000
“Where I go, there’s room for
a pair of us.

1372
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1373
01:12:02,593 --> 01:12:06,985
“Then you’d better find another
jackass,” she replied quietly.

1374
01:12:06,985 --> 01:12:10,447
I was glad that I had not asked
for a clean towel.

1375
01:12:10,447 --> 01:12:14,356
From the commercial travellers I now
separated myself, and wandered

1376
01:12:14,356 --> 01:12:16,798
alone in pleasurable aimlessness.

1377
01:12:16,798 --> 01:12:19,474
It was seven o’clock.

1378
01:12:19,474 --> 01:12:23,285
Medicine Bow stood voiceless
and unpeopled.

1379
01:12:23,285 --> 01:12:25,492
The cowboys had melted away.

1380
01:12:25,492 --> 01:12:29,452
The inhabitants were indoors,
pursuing the business or the

1381
01:12:29,452 --> 01:12:31,436
idleness of the forenoon.

1382
01:12:31,436 --> 01:12:33,740
Visible motion there was none.

1383
01:12:33,740 --> 01:12:38,246
No shell upon the dry sands could lie
more lifeless than Medicine Bow.

1384
01:12:38,246 --> 01:12:41,515
Looking in at the store,
I saw the proprietor sitting

1385
01:12:41,515 --> 01:12:42,980
with his pipe extinct.

1386
01:12:42,980 --> 01:12:46,786
Looking in at the saloon,
I saw the dealer dealing

1387
01:12:46,786 --> 01:12:48,047
dumbly to himself.

1388
01:12:48,047 --> 01:12:52,956
Up in the sky there was not a cloud nor a
bird, and on the earth the

1389
01:12:52,956 --> 01:12:56,796
lightest straw lay becalmed.

1390
01:12:56,796 --> 01:13:02,641
Once I saw the Virginian at an open door,
where the golden-haired landlady

1391
01:13:02,641 --> 01:13:03,937
stood talking with him.

1392
01:13:03,937 --> 01:13:08,421
Sometimes I strolled in the town,
and sometimes out on the plain I lay

1393
01:13:08,421 --> 01:13:11,279
down with my day dreams in the
sagebrush.

1394
01:13:11,279 --> 01:13:15,602
Pale herds of antelope were in the
distance, and near by the demure

1395
01:13:15,602 --> 01:13:18,554
prairie-dogs sat up and scrutinized me.

1396
01:13:18,554 --> 01:13:21,178
Steve, Trampas, the riot of horsemen,
my lost trunk, Uncle Hughey,

1397
01:13:21,178 --> 01:13:23,378
with his abortive brides⁠—all things
merged in my thoughts in

1398
01:13:23,378 --> 01:13:23,378
a huge, delicious indifference.

1399
01:13:23,378 --> 01:13:25,723
It was like swimming slowly at random in
an ocean that was smooth,

1400
01:13:25,723 --> 01:13:27,977
and neither too cool nor too warm.

1401
01:13:27,977 --> 01:13:31,843
And before I knew it,
five lazy imperceptible

1402
01:13:31,843 --> 01:13:34,352
hours had gone thus.

1403
01:13:34,352 --> 01:13:40,320
There was the Union Pacific train,
coming as if from shores forgotten.

1404
01:13:40,320 --> 01:13:43,502
Its approach was silent
and long drawn out.

1405
01:13:43,502 --> 01:13:46,862
I easily reached town and the platform
before it had finished

1406
01:13:46,862 --> 01:13:48,163
watering at the tank.

1407
01:13:48,163 --> 01:13:52,749
It moved up, made a short halt,
I saw my trunk come out of it,

1408
01:13:52,749 --> 01:13:58,104
and then it moved away silently as it
had come, smoking and

1409
01:13:58,104 --> 01:14:00,674
dwindling into distance unknown.

1410
01:14:00,674 --> 01:14:05,487
Beside my trunk was one other,
tied extravagantly with white ribbon.

1411
01:14:05,487 --> 01:14:09,074
The fluttering bows caught my attention,
and now I suddenly saw

1412
01:14:09,074 --> 01:14:10,995
a perfectly new sight.

1413
01:14:10,995 --> 01:14:14,995
The Virginian was further down the
platform, doubled up with laughing.

1414
01:14:14,995 --> 01:14:19,455
It was good to know that with sufficient
cause he could laugh like this;

1415
01:14:19,455 --> 01:14:23,026
a smile had thus far been his
limit of external mirth.

1416
01:14:23,026 --> 01:14:28,693
Rice now flew against my hat,
and hissing gusts of rice

1417
01:14:28,693 --> 01:14:30,831
spouted on the platform.

1418
01:14:30,831 --> 01:14:34,726
All the men left in Medicine Bow appeared
like magic, and more

1419
01:14:34,726 --> 01:14:36,621
rice choked the atmosphere.

1420
01:14:36,621 --> 01:14:40,377
Through the general clamor a cracked
voice said, “Don’t hit her

1421
01:14:40,377 --> 01:14:41,619
in the eye, boys!”

1422
01:14:41,619 --> 01:14:46,518
and Uncle Hughey rushed proudly by me
with an actual wife on his arm.

1423
01:14:46,518 --> 01:14:49,044
She could easily have
been his granddaughter.

1424
01:14:49,044 --> 01:14:51,820
They got at once into a vehicle.

1425
01:14:51,820 --> 01:14:54,712
The trunk was lifted in behind.

1426
01:14:54,712 --> 01:14:59,289
And amid cheers, rice,
shoes, and broad felicitations,

1427
01:14:59,289 --> 01:15:03,435
the pair drove out of town,
Uncle Hughey shrieking to the horses and

1428
01:15:03,435 --> 01:15:06,764
the bride waving unabashed adieus.

1429
01:15:06,764 --> 01:15:10,125
The word had come over the wires from
Laramie: “Uncle Hughey has

1430
01:15:10,125 --> 01:15:11,158
made it this time.

1431
01:15:11,158 --> 01:15:13,540
Expect him on today’s number two.”

1432
01:15:13,540 --> 01:15:15,727
And Medicine Bow had expected him.

1433
01:15:15,727 --> 01:15:18,834
Many words arose on the departure of
the new-married couple.

1434
01:15:18,834 --> 01:15:19,611
“Who’s she?”

1435
01:15:19,611 --> 01:15:20,888
“What’s he got for her?”

1436
01:15:20,888 --> 01:15:23,513
“Got a gold mine up Bear Creek.”

1437
01:15:23,513 --> 01:15:28,333
And after comment and prophecy,
Medicine Bow returned to its dinner.

1438
01:15:28,333 --> 01:15:31,135
This meal was my last here
for a long while.

1439
01:15:31,135 --> 01:15:34,841
The Virginian’s responsibility now
returned; duty drove the Judge’s

1440
01:15:34,841 --> 01:15:38,093
trustworthy man to take care of me
again.

1441
01:15:38,093 --> 01:15:42,875
He had not once sought my society of his
own accord; his distaste for what he

1442
01:15:42,875 --> 01:15:48,720
supposed me to be (I don’t exactly know
what this was) remained unshaken.

1443
01:15:48,720 --> 01:15:53,444
I have thought that matters of dress and
speech should not carry with them so

1444
01:15:53,444 --> 01:15:58,185
much mistrust in our democracy;
thieves are presumed innocent until

1445
01:15:58,185 --> 01:16:02,504
proved guilty, but a starched collar
is condemned at once.

1446
01:16:02,504 --> 01:16:05,846
Perfect civility and obligingness I
certainly did receive from the

1447
01:16:05,846 --> 01:16:08,303
Virginian, only not a word of
fellowship.

1448
01:16:08,303 --> 01:16:13,570
He harnessed the horses,
got my trunk, and gave me some advice

1449
01:16:13,570 --> 01:16:18,250
about taking provisions for our journey,
something more palatable than what food

1450
01:16:18,250 --> 01:16:20,234
we should find along the road.

1451
01:16:20,234 --> 01:16:24,152
It was well thought of,
and I bought quite a parcel of dainties,

1452
01:16:24,152 --> 01:16:28,773
feeling that he would despise
both them and me.

1453
01:16:28,773 --> 01:16:32,733
And thus I took my seat beside him,
wondering what we should manage to talk

1454
01:16:32,733 --> 01:16:36,042
about for two hundred
and sixty-three miles.

1455
01:16:36,042 --> 01:16:40,114
Farewell in those days was not
said in Cattle Land.

1456
01:16:40,114 --> 01:16:44,342
Acquaintances watched our departure with
a nod or with nothing,

1457
01:16:44,342 --> 01:16:50,156
and the nearest approach to “Goodbye”
was the proprietor’s “So-long.”

1458
01:16:50,156 --> 01:16:53,728
But I caught sight of one
farewell given without words.

1459
01:16:53,728 --> 01:16:58,060
As we drove by the eating-house,
the shade of a side window was raised,

1460
01:16:58,060 --> 01:17:00,819
and the landlady looked her
last upon the Virginian.

1461
01:17:00,819 --> 01:17:05,307
Her lips were faintly parted,
and no woman’s eyes ever said more

1462
01:17:05,307 --> 01:17:07,928
plainly, “I am one of your possessions.”

1463
01:17:07,928 --> 01:17:10,223
She had forgotten that it might be seen.

1464
01:17:10,223 --> 01:17:12,483
Her glance caught mine,
and she backed into the

1465
01:17:12,483 --> 01:17:13,664
dimness of the room.

1466
01:17:13,664 --> 01:17:19,043
What look she may have received from him,
if he gave her any at this too public

1467
01:17:19,043 --> 01:17:21,078
moment, I could not tell.

1468
01:17:21,078 --> 01:17:25,523
His eyes seemed to be upon the horses,
and he drove with the same mastering

1469
01:17:25,523 --> 01:17:28,336
ease that had roped the
wild pony yesterday.

1470
01:17:28,336 --> 01:17:34,217
We passed the ramparts of Medicine Bow⁠—
thick heaps and fringes of tin cans,

1471
01:17:34,217 --> 01:17:38,821
and shelving mounds of bottles cast
out of the saloons.

1472
01:17:38,821 --> 01:17:42,054
The sun struck these at
a hundred glittering points.

1473
01:17:42,054 --> 01:17:47,182
And in a moment we were in the clean
plains, with the prairie-dogs and the

1474
01:17:47,182 --> 01:17:48,893
pale herds of antelope.

1475
01:17:48,893 --> 01:17:55,429
The great, still air bathed us,
pure as water and strong as wine;

1476
01:17:55,429 --> 01:17:58,869
the sunlight flooded the world;
and shining upon the breast of the

1477
01:17:58,869 --> 01:18:03,885
Virginian’s flannel shirt lay a long
gold thread of hair!

1478
01:18:03,885 --> 01:18:09,112
The noisy American drummer had met
defeat, but this silent free lance

1479
01:18:09,112 --> 01:18:11,301
had been easily victorious.

1480
01:18:11,301 --> 01:18:15,502
It must have been five miles that we
travelled in silence,

1481
01:18:15,502 --> 01:18:20,418
losing and seeing the horizon among the
ceaseless waves of the earth.

1482
01:18:20,418 --> 01:18:24,105
Then I looked back, and there was
Medicine Bow, seemingly a

1483
01:18:24,105 --> 01:18:26,048
stone’s throw behind us.

1484
01:18:26,048 --> 01:18:30,766
It was a full half-hour before I looked
back again, and there sure enough

1485
01:18:30,766 --> 01:18:32,683
was always Medicine Bow.

1486
01:18:32,683 --> 01:18:37,539
A size or two smaller,
I will admit, but visible in every

1487
01:18:37,539 --> 01:18:41,983
feature, like something seen through the
wrong end of a field glass.

1488
01:18:41,983 --> 01:18:46,440
The Eastbound express was approaching the
town, and I noticed the white steam from

1489
01:18:46,440 --> 01:18:50,081
its whistle; but when the sound reached
us, the train had almost stopped.

1490
01:18:50,081 --> 01:18:55,133
And in reply to my comment upon this,
the Virginian deigned to remark that it

1491
01:18:55,133 --> 01:18:57,293
was more so in Arizona.

1492
01:18:57,293 --> 01:19:02,609
“A man come to Arizona,”
he said, “with one of them telescopes to

1493
01:19:02,609 --> 01:19:04,561
study the heavenly bodies.

1494
01:19:04,561 --> 01:19:08,106
He was a Yankee, seh,
and a right smart one, too.

1495
01:19:08,106 --> 01:19:12,983
And one night we was watchin’ for some
little old fallin’ stars that he said

1496
01:19:12,983 --> 01:19:17,742
was due, and I saw some lights movin’
along across the mesa pretty lively,

1497
01:19:17,742 --> 01:19:19,013
an’ I sang out.

1498
01:19:19,013 --> 01:19:21,828
But he told me it was just the train.

1499
01:19:21,828 --> 01:19:26,424
And I told him I didn’t know yu’ could
see the cyars that plain from his place,

1500
01:19:26,424 --> 01:19:30,157
‘Yu’ can see them,’ he said to me,
‘but it is las’ night’s

1501
01:19:30,157 --> -1:59:59,000
cyars you’re lookin’ at.’

1502
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1503
01:19:31,808 --> 01:19:35,830
At this point the Virginian spoke
severely to one of the horses.

1504
01:19:35,830 --> 01:19:39,230
“Of course,” he then resumed to me,
“that Yankee man did not mean quite all

1505
01:19:39,230 --> 01:19:40,910
he said.⁠—You, Buck!”

1506
01:19:40,910 --> 01:19:42,953
he again broke off suddenly to the horse.

1507
01:19:42,953 --> 01:19:47,350
“But Arizona, seh,” he continued,
“it cert’nly has a mos’

1508
01:19:47,350 --> 01:19:49,049
deceivin’ atmospheah.

1509
01:19:49,049 --> 01:19:52,830
Another man told me he had seen a lady
close one eye at him when he was two

1510
01:19:52,830 --> 01:19:54,270
minutes hard run from her.”

1511
01:19:54,270 --> 01:19:57,313
This time the Virginian
gave Buck the whip.

1512
01:19:57,313 --> 01:20:02,303
“What effect,” I inquired with a gravity
equal to his own, “does this

1513
01:20:02,303 --> 01:20:06,038
extraordinary foreshortening have upon
a quart of whiskey?”

1514
01:20:06,038 --> 01:20:10,995
“When it’s outside yu’, seh,
no distance looks too far to go to it.”

1515
01:20:10,995 --> 01:20:16,533
He glanced at me with an eye that held
more confidence than hitherto he had

1516
01:20:16,533 --> 01:20:18,213
been able to feel in me.

1517
01:20:18,213 --> 01:20:21,571
I had made one step in his approval.

1518
01:20:21,571 --> 01:20:23,766
But I had many yet to go.

1519
01:20:23,766 --> 01:20:28,892
This day he preferred his own thoughts to
my conversation, and so he did all the

1520
01:20:28,892 --> 01:20:32,172
days of this first journey;
while I should have greatly preferred

1521
01:20:32,172 --> 01:20:34,183
his conversation to my thoughts.

1522
01:20:34,183 --> 01:20:39,567
He dismissed some attempts that I made
upon the subject of Uncle Hughey so that

1523
01:20:39,567 --> 01:20:44,965
I had not the courage to touch upon
Trampas, and that chill brief collision

1524
01:20:44,965 --> 01:20:47,937
which might have struck
the spark of death.

1525
01:20:47,937 --> 01:20:49,007
Trampas!

1526
01:20:49,007 --> 01:20:53,477
I had forgotten him till this silent
drive I was beginning.

1527
01:20:53,477 --> 01:20:59,011
I wondered if I should ever see him,
or Steve, or any of those people again.

1528
01:20:59,011 --> 01:21:01,878
And this wonder I expressed aloud.

1529
01:21:01,878 --> 01:21:03,811
“There’s no tellin’ in this country

1530
01:21:03,811 --> 01:21:04,837
,” said the Virginian.

1531
01:21:04,837 --> 01:21:07,503
“Folks come easy, and they go easy.

1532
01:21:07,503 --> 01:21:11,617
In settled places, like back in the
States, even a poor man

1533
01:21:11,617 --> 01:21:13,217
mostly has a home.

1534
01:21:13,217 --> 01:21:17,497
Don’t care if it’s only a barrel on a
lot, the fello’ will keep frequentin’

1535
01:21:17,497 --> 01:21:20,417
that lot, and if yu’ want him
yu’ can find him.

1536
01:21:20,417 --> 01:21:23,497
But out hyeh in the sagebrush,
a man’s home is apt to

1537
01:21:23,497 --> 01:21:24,780
be his saddle blanket.

1538
01:21:24,780 --> -1:59:59,000
First thing yu’ know,
he has moved it to Texas.

1539
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1540
01:21:28,149 --> 01:21:32,074
“You have done some moving
yourself,” I suggested.

1541
01:21:32,074 --> 01:21:35,123
But this word closed his mouth.

1542
01:21:35,123 --> 01:21:39,868
“I have had a look at the country,”
he said, and we were silent again.

1543
01:21:39,868 --> 01:21:43,770
Let me, however, tell you here that he
had set out for a “look at the country”

1544
01:21:43,770 --> 01:21:46,779
at the age of fourteen;
and that by his present age of twenty-

1545
01:21:46,779 --> 01:21:52,523
four he had seen Arkansas,
Texas, New Mexico, Arizona,

1546
01:21:52,523 --> 01:21:57,890
California, Oregon, Idaho,
Montana, and Wyoming.

1547
01:21:57,890 --> 01:22:03,247
Everywhere he had taken care of himself,
and survived; nor had his strong heart

1548
01:22:03,247 --> 01:22:06,346
yet waked up to any hunger for a home.

1549
01:22:06,346 --> 01:22:10,819
Let me also tell you that he was one of
thousands drifting and living thus,

1550
01:22:10,819 --> 01:22:14,960
but (as you shall learn)
one in a thousand.

1551
01:22:14,960 --> 01:22:20,025
Medicine Bow did not forever
remain in sight.

1552
01:22:20,025 --> 01:22:24,865
When next I thought of it and looked
behind, nothing was there but the road

1553
01:22:24,865 --> 01:22:30,637
we had come; it lay like a ship’s wake
across the huge ground

1554
01:22:30,637 --> 01:22:32,459
swell of the earth.

1555
01:22:32,459 --> 01:22:35,381
We were swallowed in a vast solitude.

1556
01:22:35,381 --> 01:22:38,459
A little while before sunset,
a cabin came in view;

1557
01:22:38,459 --> 01:22:40,579
and here we passed our first night.

1558
01:22:40,579 --> 01:22:44,085
Two young men lived here,
tending their cattle.

1559
01:22:44,085 --> 01:22:45,952
They were fond of animals.

1560
01:22:45,952 --> 01:22:51,677
By the stable a chained coyote rushed
nervously in a circle,

1561
01:22:51,677 --> 01:22:57,233
or sat on its haunches and snapped at
gifts of food ungraciously.

1562
01:22:57,233 --> 01:23:01,713
A tame young elk walked in and out of the
cabin door, and during supper it tried

1563
01:23:01,713 --> 01:23:03,443
to push me off my chair.

1564
01:23:03,443 --> 01:23:08,926
A half-tame mountain sheep practised
jumping from the ground to the roof.

1565
01:23:08,926 --> 01:23:16,746
The cabin was papered with posters of a
circus, and skins of bear and silver fox

1566
01:23:16,746 --> 01:23:18,157
lay upon the floor.

1567
01:23:18,157 --> 01:23:22,794
Until nine o’clock one man talked to the
Virginian, and one played gayly upon a

1568
01:23:22,794 --> 01:23:26,430
concertina; and then we all went to bed.

1569
01:23:26,430 --> 01:23:30,703
The air was like December,
but in my blankets and a buffalo robe I

1570
01:23:30,703 --> 01:23:34,228
kept warm, and luxuriated in
the Rocky Mountain silence.

1571
01:23:34,228 --> 01:23:37,969
Going to wash before breakfast at
sunrise, I found needles of

1572
01:23:37,969 --> 01:23:39,044
ice in a pail.

1573
01:23:39,044 --> 01:23:44,722
Yet it was hard to remember that this
quiet, open, splendid wilderness (with

1574
01:23:44,722 --> 01:23:50,706
not a peak in sight just here) was
six thousand feet high.

1575
01:23:50,706 --> 01:23:55,117
And when breakfast was over there was no
December left; and by the time the

1576
01:23:55,117 --> 01:23:59,164
Virginian and I were ten miles upon our
way, it was June.

1577
01:23:59,164 --> 01:24:04,667
But always every breath that I breathed
was pure as water and strong as wine.

1578
01:24:04,667 --> 01:24:07,234
We never passed a human being this day.

1579
01:24:07,234 --> 01:24:12,894
Some wild cattle rushed up to us and away
from us; antelope stared at us from a

1580
01:24:12,894 --> 01:24:18,124
hundred yards; coyotes ran skulking
through the sagebrush to watch us from a

1581
01:24:18,124 --> 01:24:22,605
hill; at our noon meal we killed a
rattlesnake and shot some young sage

1582
01:24:22,605 --> 01:24:27,565
chickens, which were good at supper,
roasted at our campfire.

1583
01:24:27,565 --> 01:24:34,361
By half-past eight we were asleep beneath
the stars, and by half-past four I was

1584
01:24:34,361 --> 01:24:36,390
drinking coffee and shivering.

1585
01:24:36,390 --> 01:24:41,957
The horse, Buck, was hard to
catch this second morning.

1586
01:24:41,957 --> 01:24:47,075
Whether some hills that we were now in
had excited him, or whether the better

1587
01:24:47,075 --> 01:24:49,515
water up here had caused an
effervescence in his

1588
01:24:49,515 --> 01:24:51,517
spirits, I cannot say.

1589
01:24:51,517 --> 01:24:56,149
But I was as hot as July by the time we
had him safe in harness,

1590
01:24:56,149 --> 01:24:58,939
or, rather, unsafe in harness.

1591
01:24:58,939 --> 01:25:04,554
For Buck, in the mysterious language of
horses, now taught wickedness to his

1592
01:25:04,554 --> 01:25:09,867
side partner, and about eleven o’clock
they laid their evil heads together and

1593
01:25:09,867 --> 01:25:13,079
decided to break our necks.

1594
01:25:13,079 --> 01:25:18,330
We were passing, I have said,
through a range of demi-mountains.

1595
01:25:18,330 --> 01:25:24,295
It was a little country where trees grew,
water ran, and the plains were shut

1596
01:25:24,295 --> 01:25:25,359
out for a while.

1597
01:25:25,359 --> 01:25:28,855
The road had steep places in it,
and places here and there where you

1598
01:25:28,855 --> 01:25:33,833
could fall off and go bounding to
the bottom among stones.

1599
01:25:33,833 --> 01:25:38,667
But Buck, for some reason,
did not think these opportunities

1600
01:25:38,667 --> 01:25:39,726
good enough for him.

1601
01:25:39,726 --> 01:25:42,907
He selected a more theatrical moment.

1602
01:25:42,907 --> 01:25:51,312
We emerged from a narrow canyon suddenly
upon five hundred cattle and some

1603
01:25:51,312 --> 01:25:54,772
cowboys branding calves by a
fire in a corral.

1604
01:25:54,772 --> 01:25:57,822
It was a sight that Buck knew by heart.

1605
01:25:57,822 --> 01:26:00,873
He instantly treated it
like an appalling phenomenon.

1606
01:26:00,873 --> 01:26:06,192
I saw him kick seven ways;
I saw Muggins kick five ways;

1607
01:26:06,192 --> 01:26:10,695
our furious motion snapped my
spine like a whip.

1608
01:26:10,695 --> 01:26:12,487
I grasped the seat.

1609
01:26:12,487 --> 01:26:14,586
Something gave a forlorn jingle.

1610
01:26:14,586 --> 01:26:15,946
It was the brake.

1611
01:26:15,946 --> 01:26:17,042
“Don’t jump!”

1612
01:26:17,042 --> 01:26:18,834
commanded the trustworthy man.

1613
01:26:18,834 --> 01:26:23,067
“No,” I said, as my hat flew off.

1614
01:26:23,067 --> 01:26:26,771
Help was too far away to
do anything for us.

1615
01:26:26,771 --> 01:26:31,454
We passed scatheless through a part of
the cattle, I saw their horns

1616
01:26:31,454 --> 01:26:32,792
and backs go by.

1617
01:26:32,792 --> 01:26:37,076
Some earth crumbled, and we plunged
downward into water rocking among

1618
01:26:37,076 --> 01:26:41,290
stones, and upward again through
