2547
02:20:23,946 --> 02:20:25,142
of the next chapter.

2548
02:20:25,142 --> 02:20:26,230
CHAPTER VIII

2549
02:20:26,230 --> 02:20:27,683
The Sincere Spinster

2550
02:20:27,683 --> 02:20:31,764
I do not know with which of
the two estimates⁠—Mr.

2551
02:20:31,764 --> 02:20:35,151
Taylor’s or the Virginian’s⁠—you agreed.

2552
02:20:35,151 --> 02:20:39,693
Did you think that Miss Mary Stark Wood
of Bennington, Vermont,

2553
02:20:39,693 --> 02:20:41,824
was forty years of age?

2554
02:20:41,824 --> 02:20:44,327
That would have been an error.

2555
02:20:44,327 --> 02:20:48,727
At the time she wrote the letter to Mrs.
Balaam, of which letter certain portions

2556
02:20:48,727 --> 02:20:53,333
have been quoted in these pages,
she was in her twenty-first year;

2557
02:20:53,333 --> 02:20:56,182
or, to be more precise,
she had been twenty some

2558
02:20:56,182 --> 02:20:57,582
eight months previous.

2559
02:20:57,582 --> 02:21:03,502
Now, it is not usual for young ladies of
twenty to contemplate a journey of

2560
02:21:03,502 --> 02:21:09,522
nearly two thousand miles to a country
where Indians and wild animals live

2561
02:21:09,522 --> 02:21:15,755
unchained, unless they are to make such
journey in company with a protector,

2562
02:21:15,755 --> 02:21:22,461
or are going to a protector’s arms
at the other end.

2563
02:21:22,461 --> 02:21:30,006
Nor is school teaching on Bear Creek a
usual ambition for such young ladies.

2564
02:21:30,006 --> 02:21:35,142
But Miss Mary Stark Wood was not a usual
young lady for two reasons.

2565
02:21:35,142 --> 02:21:37,561
First, there was her descent.

2566
02:21:37,561 --> 02:21:41,848
Had she so wished, she could have
belonged to any number of those

2567
02:21:41,848 --> 02:21:46,295
patriotic societies of which our
American ears have grown accustomed

2568
02:21:46,295 --> 02:21:47,704
to hear so much.

2569
02:21:47,704 --> 02:21:51,646
She could have been enrolled in the
Boston Tea Party, the Ethan Allen

2570
02:21:51,646 --> 02:21:57,194
Ticonderogas, the Green Mountain
Daughters, the Saratoga Sacred Circle,

2571
02:21:57,194 --> 02:22:00,561
and the Confederated
Colonial Chatelaines.

2572
02:22:00,561 --> 02:22:04,987
She traced direct descent from the
historic lady whose name she bore,

2573
02:22:04,987 --> 02:22:09,556
that Molly Stark who was not a widow
after the battle where her lord,

2574
02:22:09,556 --> 02:22:15,538
her Captain John, battled so bravely as
to send his name thrilling down through

2575
02:22:15,538 --> 02:22:19,500
the blood of generations of schoolboys.

2576
02:22:19,500 --> 02:22:25,538
This ancestress was her chief claim to be
a member of those shining societies

2577
02:22:25,538 --> 02:22:26,985
which I have enumerated.

2578
02:22:26,985 --> 02:22:31,945
But she had been willing to join none of
them, although invitations to do so were

2579
02:22:31,945 --> 02:22:33,680
by no means lacking.

2580
02:22:33,680 --> 02:22:35,731
I cannot tell you her reason.

2581
02:22:35,731 --> 02:22:37,729
Still, I can tell you this.

2582
02:22:37,729 --> 02:22:41,649
When these societies were much spoken of
in her presence, her very sprightly

2583
02:22:41,649 --> 02:22:46,170
countenance became more sprightly,
and she added her words of praise or

2584
02:22:46,170 --> 02:22:48,745
respect to the general chorus.

2585
02:22:48,745 --> 02:22:52,179
But when she received an invitation to
join one of these bodies,

2586
02:22:52,179 --> 02:22:55,835
her countenance, as she read the
missive, would assume an expression

2587
02:22:55,835 --> 02:23:00,462
which was known to her friends as
“sticking her nose in the air.”

2588
02:23:00,462 --> 02:23:04,360
I do not think that Molly’s reason for
refusing to join could have been

2589
02:23:04,360 --> 02:23:05,438
a truly good one.

2590
02:23:05,438 --> 02:23:09,480
I should add that her most precious
possession⁠—a treasure which accompanied

2591
02:23:09,480 --> 02:23:14,316
her even if she went away for only one
night’s absence⁠—was an heirloom,

2592
02:23:14,316 --> 02:23:19,074
a little miniature portrait of the old
Molly Stark, painted when that far-off

2593
02:23:19,074 --> 02:23:22,218
dame must have been scarce
more than twenty.

2594
02:23:22,218 --> 02:23:27,693
And when each summer the young Molly went
to Dunbarton, New Hampshire,

2595
02:23:27,693 --> 02:23:34,100
to pay her established family visit to
the last survivors of her connection who

2596
02:23:34,100 --> 02:23:38,580
bore the name of Stark,
no word that she heard in the Dunbarton

2597
02:23:38,580 --> 02:23:44,745
houses pleased her so much as when a
certain great-aunt would take her by the

2598
02:23:44,745 --> 02:23:49,488
hand, and, after looking with fond
intentness at her, pronounce:⁠—

2599
02:23:49,488 --> -1:59:59,000
“My dear, you’re getting more like the
General’s wife every year you live.

2600
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2601
02:23:56,102 --> 02:23:59,904
“I suppose you mean my nose,”
Molly would then reply.

2602
02:23:59,904 --> 02:24:02,346
“Nonsense, child.

2603
02:24:02,346 --> 02:24:05,946
You have the family length of nose,
and I’ve never heard that

2604
02:24:05,946 --> 02:24:07,233
it has disgraced us.”

2605
02:24:07,233 --> 02:24:09,674
“But I don’t think I’m
tall enough for it.”

2606
02:24:09,674 --> 02:24:13,233
“There now, run to your room,
and dress for tea.

2607
02:24:13,233 --> -1:59:59,000
The Starks have always been punctual.

2608
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2609
02:24:15,643 --> 02:24:19,691
And after this annual conversation,
Molly would run to her room,

2610
02:24:19,691 --> 02:24:23,961
and there in its privacy,
even at the risk of falling below the

2611
02:24:23,961 --> 02:24:29,089
punctuality of the Starks,
she would consult two objects for quite

2612
02:24:29,089 --> 02:24:31,801
a minute before she began to dress.

2613
02:24:31,801 --> 02:24:36,646
These objects, as you have already
correctly guessed, were the miniature of

2614
02:24:36,646 --> 02:24:40,088
the General’s wife and the looking
glass.

2615
02:24:40,088 --> 02:24:44,081
So much for Miss Molly
Stark Wood’s descent.

2616
02:24:44,081 --> 02:24:48,797
The second reason why she was not a usual
girl was her character.

2617
02:24:48,797 --> 02:24:55,246
This character was the result of pride
and family pluck battling

2618
02:24:55,246 --> 02:24:56,782
with family hardship.

2619
02:24:56,782 --> 02:25:01,046
Just one year before she was to be
presented to the world⁠—not the great

2620
02:25:01,046 --> 02:25:04,766
metropolitan world, but a world that
would have made her welcome and done her

2621
02:25:04,766 --> 02:25:10,749
homage at its little dances and little
dinners in Troy and Rutland and

2622
02:25:10,749 --> 02:25:16,130
Burlington⁠—fortune had turned her
back upon the Woods.

2623
02:25:16,130 --> 02:25:19,809
Their possessions had never been great
ones; but they had sufficed.

2624
02:25:19,809 --> 02:25:24,679
From generation to generation the family
had gone to school like gentlefolk,

2625
02:25:24,679 --> 02:25:29,720
dressed like gentlefolk,
used the speech and ways of gentlefolk,

2626
02:25:29,720 --> 02:25:32,698
and as gentlefolk lived and died.

2627
02:25:32,698 --> 02:25:34,832
And now the mills failed.

2628
02:25:34,832 --> 02:25:39,694
Instead of thinking about her first
evening dress, Molly found pupils to

2629
02:25:39,694 --> 02:25:41,986
whom she could give music lessons.

2630
02:25:41,986 --> 02:25:45,641
She found handkerchiefs that she
could embroider with initials.

2631
02:25:45,641 --> 02:25:49,740
And she found fruit that she
could make into preserves.

2632
02:25:49,740 --> 02:25:54,060
That machine called the typewriter was
then in existence, but the day of women

2633
02:25:54,060 --> 02:25:59,017
typewriters had as yet scarcely begun to
dawn, else I think Molly would have

2634
02:25:59,017 --> 02:26:03,094
preferred this occupation to the
handkerchiefs and the preserves.

2635
02:26:03,094 --> 02:26:07,616
There were people in Bennington who
“wondered how Miss Wood could go about

2636
02:26:07,616 --> 02:26:12,357
from house to house teaching the piano,
and she a lady.”

2637
02:26:12,357 --> 02:26:17,117
There always have been such people,
I suppose, because the world must always

2638
02:26:17,117 --> 02:26:18,321
have a rubbish heap.

2639
02:26:18,321 --> 02:26:23,002
But we need not dwell upon them further
than to mention one other remark

2640
02:26:23,002 --> 02:26:26,230
of theirs regarding Molly.

2641
02:26:26,230 --> 02:26:31,821
They all with one voice declared that Sam
Bannett was good enough for anybody who

2642
02:26:31,821 --> 02:26:36,296
did fancy embroidery at
five cents a letter.

2643
02:26:36,296 --> 02:26:41,034
“I dare say he had a great-grandmother
quite as good as hers,”

2644
02:26:41,034 --> 02:26:45,282
remarked Mrs. Flynt,
the wife of the Baptist minister.

2645
02:26:45,282 --> 02:26:50,111
“That’s entirely possible,”
returned the Episcopal rector of Hoosic,

2646
02:26:50,111 --> 02:26:53,275
“only we don’t happen to
know who she was.”

2647
02:26:53,275 --> 02:26:55,484
The rector was a friend of Molly’s.

2648
02:26:55,484 --> 02:26:58,828
After this little observation,
Mrs. Flynt said no more,

2649
02:26:58,828 --> 02:27:03,865
but continued her purchases in the store
