CHAPTER IX

2705
02:30:00,693 --> 02:30:02,791
The Spinster Meets the Unknown

2706
02:30:02,791 --> 02:30:06,933
On a Monday noon a small company of
horsemen strung out along the trail from

2707
02:30:06,933 --> 02:30:11,205
Sunk Creek to gather cattle over their
allotted sweep of range.

2708
02:30:11,205 --> 02:30:15,778
Spring was backward, and they,
as they rode galloping and gathering

2709
02:30:15,778 --> 02:30:20,709
upon the cold week’s work,
cursed cheerily and occasionally sang.

2710
02:30:20,709 --> 02:30:25,982
The Virginian was grave in bearing and of
infrequent speech; but he kept a song

2711
02:30:25,982 --> 02:30:29,360
going⁠—a matter of some
seventy-nine verses.

2712
02:30:29,360 --> 02:30:33,204
Seventy-eight were quite unprintable,
and rejoiced his brother

2713
02:30:33,204 --> 02:30:35,847
cowpunchers monstrously.

2714
02:30:35,847 --> 02:30:40,249
They, knowing him to be a singular man,
forebore ever to press him,

2715
02:30:40,249 --> 02:30:43,758
and awaited his own humor,
lest he should weary of the lyric;

2716
02:30:43,758 --> 02:30:47,681
and when after a day of silence
apparently saturnine,

2717
02:30:47,681 --> 02:30:50,497
he would lift his gentle
voice and begin:⁠—

2718
02:30:50,497 --> 02:30:55,483
“If you go to monkey with my Looloo girl,
