02:31:43,213 --> 02:31:45,986
They stopped for a meal
at an old comrade’s.

2731
02:31:45,986 --> 02:31:49,599
They looked over his gate,
and there he was pattering

2732
02:31:49,599 --> 02:31:51,181
among garden furrows.

2733
02:31:51,181 --> 02:31:52,639
“Pickin’ nosegays?”

2734
02:31:52,639 --> 02:31:56,601
inquired the Virginian and the old
comrade asked if they could not

2735
02:31:56,601 --> 02:31:59,666
recognize potatoes except in the dish.

2736
02:31:59,666 --> 02:32:04,724
But he grinned sheepishly at them,
too, because they knew that he had not

2737
02:32:04,724 --> 02:32:06,727
always lived in a garden.

2738
02:32:06,727 --> 02:32:10,044
Then he took them into his house,
where they saw an object crawling on the

2739
02:32:10,044 --> 02:32:12,670
floor with a handful of sulphur matches.

2740
02:32:12,670 --> 02:32:17,296
He began to remove the matches,
but stopped in alarm at the vociferous

2741
02:32:17,296 --> 02:32:20,737
result; and his wife looked in from the
kitchen to caution him

2742
02:32:20,737 --> 02:32:22,885
about humoring little Christopher.

2743
02:32:22,885 --> 02:32:27,268
When she beheld the matches she was
aghast but when she saw her baby grow

2744
02:32:27,268 --> 02:32:31,219
quiet in the arms of the Virginian,
she smiled at that cowpuncher and

2745
02:32:31,219 --> 02:32:32,525
returned to her kitchen.

2746
02:32:32,525 --> 02:32:34,954
Then the Virginian slowly spoke again:⁠—

2747
02:32:34,954 --> 02:32:38,436
“How many little strangers
have yu’ got, James?”

2748
02:32:38,436 --> 02:32:39,382
“Only two.”

2749
02:32:39,382 --> 02:32:39,970
“My!

2750
02:32:39,970 --> 02:32:42,158
Ain’t it most three years
since yu’ maried?

2751
02:32:42,158 --> -1:59:59,000
Yu’ mustn’t let time creep
ahaid o’ yu’, James.

2752
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2753
02:32:47,728 --> 02:32:52,009
The father once more grinned at his
guests, who themselves turned sheepish

2754
02:32:52,009 --> 02:32:57,655
and polite; for Mrs. Westfall came in,
brisk and hearty, and set the

2755
02:32:57,655 --> 02:32:58,976
meat upon the table.

2756
02:32:58,976 --> 02:33:01,667
After that, it was she who talked.

2757
02:33:01,667 --> 02:33:06,943
The guests ate scrupulously,
muttering, “Yes, ma’am,”

2758
02:33:06,943 --> 02:33:12,017
and “No, ma’am,” in their plates,
while their hostess told them of

2759
02:33:12,017 --> 02:33:17,781
increasing families upon Bear Creek,
and the expected schoolteacher,

2760
02:33:17,781 --> 02:33:25,154
and little Alfred’s early teething,
and how it was time for all of them to

2761
02:33:25,154 --> 02:33:28,325
become husbands like James.

2762
02:33:28,325 --> 02:33:33,240
The bachelors of the saddle listened,
always diffident, but eating heartily to

2763
02:33:33,240 --> 02:33:44,972
the end; and soon after they rode away
in a thoughtful clump.

2764
02:33:44,972 --> 02:33:49,095
The wives of Bear Creek were few as yet,
and the homes scattered;

2765
02:33:49,095 --> 02:33:55,439
the schoolhouse was only a sprig on the
vast face of a world of elk and bear and

2766
02:33:55,439 --> 02:34:00,280
uncertain Indians; but that night,
when the earth near the fire was

2767
02:34:00,280 --> 02:34:05,332
littered with the cowpunchers’ beds,
the Virginian was heard drawling to

2768
02:34:05,332 --> 02:34:07,892
himself: “Alfred and Christopher.

2769
02:34:07,892 --> 02:34:09,217
Oh, sugar!”

2770
02:34:09,217 --> 02:34:13,213
They found pleasure in the delicately
chosen shade of this oath.

2771
02:34:13,213 --> 02:34:18,133
He also recited to them a new verse about
how he took his Looloo girl to the

2772
02:34:18,133 --> 02:34:23,326
schoolhouse for to learn her A.B.C.;
and as it was quite original and

2773
02:34:23,326 --> 02:34:28,126
unprintable, the camp laughed and swore
joyfully, and rolled in its blankets to

2774
02:34:28,126 --> 02:34:29,897
sleep under the stars.

2775
02:34:29,897 --> 02:34:35,241
Upon a Monday noon likewise (for things
will happen so) some tearful people in

2776
02:34:35,241 --> 02:34:39,002
petticoats waved handkerchiefs at a
train that was just leaving

2777
02:34:39,002 --> 02:34:40,208
Bennington, Vermont.

2778
02:34:40,208 --> 02:34:44,698
A girl’s face smiled back at them once,
and withdrew quickly,

2779
02:34:44,698 --> 02:34:47,096
for they must not see the smile die
away.

2780
02:34:47,096 --> 02:34:51,628
She had with her a little money,
a few clothes, and in her mind a rigid

2781
02:34:51,628 --> 02:34:57,932
determination neither to be a burden to
her mother nor to give in

2782
02:34:57,932 --> 02:35:00,557
to that mother’s desires.

2783
02:35:00,557 --> 02:35:06,005
Absence alone would enable her to
carry out this determination.

2784
02:35:06,005 --> 02:35:10,096
Beyond these things, she possessed not
much except spelling-books,

2785
02:35:10,096 --> 02:35:13,764
a colonial miniature,
and that craving for the unknown

2786
02:35:13,764 --> 02:35:15,500
which has been mentioned.

2787
02:35:15,500 --> 02:35:22,243
If the ancestors that we carry shut up
inside us take turns in dictating to us

2788
02:35:22,243 --> 02:35:27,396
our actions and our state of mind,
undoubtedly Grandmother Stark was

2789
02:35:27,396 --> 02:35:31,036
empress of Molly’s spirit
upon this Monday.

2790
02:35:31,036 --> 02:35:36,990
At Hoosic Junction, which came soon,
she passed the up-train bound back to

2791
02:35:36,990 --> 02:35:41,000
her home, and seeing the engineer and
the conductor⁠—faces that she knew

2792
02:35:41,000 --> 02:35:45,184
well⁠—her courage nearly failed her,
and she shut her eyes against this

2793
02:35:45,184 --> 02:35:49,128
glimpse of the familiar things
that she was leaving.

2794
02:35:49,128 --> 02:35:53,265
To keep herself steady she gripped
tightly a little bunch of

2795
02:35:53,265 --> 02:35:54,742
flowers in her hand.

2796
02:35:54,742 --> 02:35:59,825
But something caused her eyes to open;
and there before her stood Sam Bannett,

2797
02:35:59,825 --> 02:36:03,945
asking if he might accompany her so
far as Rotterdam Junction.

2798
02:36:03,945 --> 02:36:04,613
“No!”

2799
02:36:04,613 --> 02:36:08,685
she told him with a severity born from
the struggle she was

2800
02:36:08,685 --> 02:36:09,932
making with her grief.

2801
02:36:09,932 --> 02:36:11,685
“Not a mile with me.

2802
02:36:11,685 --> 02:36:14,208
Not to Eagle Bridge.

2803
02:36:14,208 --> -1:59:59,000
Goodbye.

2804
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2805
02:36:16,528 --> 02:36:19,670
And Sam⁠—what did he do?

2806
02:36:19,670 --> 02:36:22,411
He obeyed her, I should like to
be sorry for him.

2807
02:36:22,411 --> 02:36:25,931
But obedience was not a lover’s part here.

2808
02:36:25,931 --> 02:36:30,158
He hesitated, the golden moment hung
hovering, the conductor

2809
02:36:30,158 --> 02:36:32,534
cried “All aboard!”

2810
02:36:32,534 --> 02:36:38,035
the train went, and there on the platform
stood obedient Sam, with his golden

2811
02:36:38,035 --> 02:36:39,602
moment gone like a butterfly.

2812
02:36:39,602 --> 02:36:42,887
After Rotterdam Junction,
which was some forty minutes farther,

2813
02:36:42,887 --> 02:36:47,321
Molly Wood sat bravely up in the through
car, dwelling upon the unknown.

2814
02:36:47,321 --> 02:36:51,368
She thought that she had attained it in
Ohio, on Tuesday morning,

2815
02:36:51,368 --> 02:36:53,477
and wrote a letter about
it to Bennington.

2816
02:36:53,477 --> 02:36:57,479
On Wednesday afternoon she felt sure,
and wrote a letter much more

2817
02:36:57,479 --> 02:36:58,796
picturesque.

2818
02:36:58,796 --> 02:37:03,023
But on the following day,
after breakfast at North Platte,

2819
02:37:03,023 --> 02:37:07,963
Nebraska, she wrote a very long letter
indeed, and told them that she had seen

2820
02:37:07,963 --> 02:37:13,206
a black pig on a white pile of buffalo
bones, catching drops of water in the

2821
02:37:13,206 --> 02:37:17,420
air as they fell from the railroad tank.

2822
02:37:17,420 --> 02:37:20,937
She also wrote that trees
were extraordinarily scarce.

2823
02:37:20,937 --> 02:37:27,470
Each hour westward from the pig confirmed
this opinion, and when she left the

2824
02:37:27,470 --> 02:37:32,810
train at Rock Creek,
late upon that fourth night⁠—in those

2825
02:37:32,810 --> 02:37:37,370
days the trains were slower⁠—she knew
that she had really attained the

2826
02:37:37,370 --> 02:37:43,153
unknown, and sent an expensive telegram
to say that she was quite well.

2827
02:37:43,153 --> 02:37:47,054
At six in the morning the stage drove
away into the sagebrush,

2828
02:37:47,054 --> 02:37:50,914
with her as its only passenger;
and by sundown she had passed through

2829
02:37:50,914 --> 02:37:52,990
some of the primitive
perils of the world.

2830
02:37:52,990 --> 02:37:58,719
The second team, virgin to harness,
and displeased with this novelty,

2831
02:37:58,719 --> 02:38:02,292
tried to take it off,
and went down to the bottom of a gully

2832
02:38:02,292 --> 02:38:05,989
on its eight hind legs,
while Miss Wood sat mute and

2833
02:38:05,989 --> 02:38:07,788
unflinching beside the driver.

2834
02:38:07,788 --> 02:38:13,812
Therefore he, when it was over,
and they on the proper road again,

2835
02:38:13,812 --> 02:38:19,053
invited her earnestly to be his wife
during many of the next fifteen miles,

2836
02:38:19,053 --> 02:38:24,454
and told her of his snug cabin and his
horses and his mine.

2837
02:38:24,454 --> 02:38:30,839
Then she got down and rode inside,
Independence and Grandmother Stark

2838
02:38:30,839 --> 02:38:32,286
shining in her eye.

2839
02:38:32,286 --> 02:38:36,489
At Point of Rocks, where they had supper
and his drive ended,

2840
02:38:36,489 --> 02:38:40,712
her face distracted his heart,
and he told her once more about his

2841
02:38:40,712 --> 02:38:43,679
cabin, and lamentably hoped
she would remember him.

2842
02:38:43,679 --> 02:38:48,230
She answered sweetly that she would try,
and gave him her hand.

2843
02:38:48,230 --> 02:38:53,749
After all, he was a frank-looking boy,
who had paid her the highest compliment

2844
02:38:53,749 --> 02:39:00,279
that a boy (or a man for that matter)
knows; and it is said that Molly Stark,

2845
02:39:00,279 --> 02:39:03,320
in her day, was not a New Woman.

2846
02:39:03,320 --> 02:39:08,060
The new driver banished the first one
from the maiden’s mind.

2847
02:39:08,060 --> 02:39:11,672
He was not a frank-looking boy,
and he had been taking whiskey.

2848
02:39:11,672 --> 02:39:14,575
All night long he took it,
while his passenger,

2849
02:39:14,575 --> 02:39:19,080
helpless and sleepless inside the
lurching stage, sat as upright as

2850
02:39:19,080 --> 02:39:20,480
she possibly could; nor

2851
02:39:20,480 --> 02:39:23,389
did the voices that she heard
at Drybone reassure her.

2852
02:39:23,389 --> 02:39:27,820
Sunrise found the white stage lurching
eternally on across the alkali,

2853
02:39:27,820 --> 02:39:32,824
with a driver and a bottle on the box,
and a pale girl staring out at the

2854
02:39:32,824 --> 02:39:38,698
plain, and knotting in her handkerchief
some utterly dead flowers.

2855
02:39:38,698 --> 02:39:41,924
They came to a river where the man
bungled over the ford.

2856
02:39:41,924 --> 02:39:45,599
Two wheels sank down over an edge,
and the canvas toppled

2857
02:39:45,599 --> 02:39:47,149
like a descending kite.

2858
02:39:47,149 --> 02:39:52,965
The ripple came sucking through the upper
spokes, and as she felt the seat careen,

2859
02:39:52,965 --> 02:39:57,578
she put out her head and tremulously
asked if anything was wrong.

2860
02:39:57,578 --> 02:40:01,437
But the driver was addressing his team
with much language, and

2861
02:40:01,437 --> 02:40:03,567
also with the lash.

2862
02:40:03,567 --> 02:40:08,918
Then a tall rider appeared close against
the buried axles, and took her out of

2863
02:40:08,918 --> 02:40:13,850
the stage on his horse so
suddenly that she screamed.

2864
02:40:13,850 --> 02:40:19,048
She felt splashes, saw a swimming flood,
and found herself lifted

2865
02:40:19,048 --> 02:40:20,534
down upon the shore.

2866
02:40:20,534 --> 02:40:24,300
The rider said something to her about
cheering up, and its being all right,

2867
02:40:24,300 --> 02:40:28,041
but her wits were stock-still,
so she did not speak and thank him.

2868
02:40:28,041 --> 02:40:32,719
After four days of train and thirty hours
of stage, she was having a little too

2869
02:40:32,719 --> 02:40:34,679
much of the unknown at once.

2870
02:40:34,679 --> 02:40:40,571
Then the tall man gently withdrew leaving
her to become herself again.

2871
02:40:40,571 --> 02:40:44,782
She limply regarded the river pouring
round the slanted stage,

2872
02:40:44,782 --> 02:40:49,491
and a number of horsemen with ropes,
who righted the vehicle,

2873
02:40:49,491 --> 02:40:53,380
and got it quickly to dry land,
and disappeared at once with a herd of

2874
02:40:53,380 --> 02:40:55,681
cattle, uttering lusty yells.

2875
02:40:55,681 --> 02:41:00,268
She saw the tall one delaying beside
the driver, and speaking.

2876
02:41:00,268 --> 02:41:03,881
He spoke so quietly that not a word
reached her, until of a sudden

2877
02:41:03,881 --> 02:41:06,192
the driver protested loudly.

2878
02:41:06,192 --> 02:41:09,929
The man had thrown something,
which turned out to be a bottle.

2879
02:41:09,929 --> 02:41:13,128
This twisted loftily and
dived into the stream.

2880
02:41:13,128 --> 02:41:17,642
He said something more to the driver,
then put his hand on the saddle-horn,

2881
02:41:17,642 --> 02:41:22,762
looked half-lingeringly at the passenger
on the bank, dropped his grave eyes from

2882
02:41:22,762 --> 02:41:29,386
hers, and swinging upon his horse,
was gone just as the passenger opened

2883
02:41:29,386 --> 02:41:35,179
her mouth and with inefficient voice
murmured, “Oh, thank you!”

2884
02:41:35,179 --> 02:41:36,700
at his departing back.

2885
02:41:36,700 --> 02:41:39,858
The driver drove up now,
a chastened creature.

2886
02:41:39,858 --> 02:41:44,332
He helped Miss Wood in,
and inquired after her welfare with a

2887
02:41:44,332 --> 02:41:49,445
hanging head; then meek as his own
drenched horses, he climbed back to his

2888
02:41:49,445 --> 02:41:55,384
reins, and nursed the stage on toward
the Bow Leg Mountains much as if it

2889
02:41:55,384 --> 02:41:56,739
had been a perambulator.

2890
02:41:56,739 --> 02:42:00,464
As for Miss Wood, she sat recovering,
and she wondered what the man on the

2891
02:42:00,464 --> 02:42:02,342
horse must think of her.

2892
02:42:02,342 --> 02:42:06,917
She knew that she was not ungrateful,
and that if he had given her an

2893
02:42:06,917 --> 02:42:10,487
opportunity she would
have explained to him.

2894
02:42:10,487 --> 02:42:16,391
If he supposed that she did not
appreciate his act⁠—Here into the midst

2895
02:42:16,391 --> 02:42:21,214
of these meditations came an abrupt
memory that she had screamed⁠—she could

2896
02:42:21,214 --> 02:42:23,095
not be sure when.

2897
02:42:23,095 --> 02:42:26,375
She rehearsed the adventure from the
beginning, and found one or two further

2898
02:42:26,375 --> 02:42:30,897
uncertainties⁠—how it had all been while
she was on the horse, for instance.

2899
02:42:30,897 --> 02:42:36,853
It was confusing to determine precisely
what she had done with her arms.

2900
02:42:36,853 --> 02:42:39,182
She knew where one of his arms had been.

2901
02:42:39,182 --> 02:42:43,469
And the handkerchief with
the flowers was gone.

2902
02:42:43,469 --> 02:42:47,264
She made a few rapid dives
in search of it.

2903
02:42:47,264 --> 02:42:51,525
Had she, or had she not,
seen him putting something in his

2904
02:42:51,525 --> 02:42:52,065
pocket?

2905
02:42:52,065 --> 02:42:56,010
And why had she behaved so unlike herself?

2906
02:42:56,010 --> 02:43:01,529
In a few miles Miss Wood entertained
sentiments of maidenly resentment toward

2907
02:43:01,529 --> 02:43:04,459
her rescuer, and of maidenly hope
to see him again.

2908
02:43:04,459 --> 02:43:09,773
To that river crossing he came again,
alone, when the days were growing short.

2909
02:43:09,773 --> 02:43:14,624
The ford was dry sand,
and the stream a winding lane of

2910
02:43:14,624 --> 02:43:15,367
shingle.

2911
02:43:15,367 --> 02:43:20,786
He found a pool⁠—pools always survive the
year round in this stream⁠—and having

2912
02:43:20,786 --> 02:43:24,999
watered his pony, he lunched near the
spot to which he had borne the

2913
02:43:24,999 --> 02:43:26,926
frightened passenger that day.

2914
02:43:26,926 --> 02:43:30,969
Where the flowing current had been he
sat, regarding the now

2915
02:43:30,969 --> 02:43:32,849
extremely safe channel.

2916
02:43:32,849 --> 02:43:36,853
“She cert’nly wouldn’t need to grip me so
close this mawnin’,” he said,

2917
02:43:36,853 --> 02:43:38,681
as he pondered over his meal.

2918
02:43:38,681 --> 02:43:43,442
“I reckon it will mightily astonish her
when I tell her how harmless

2919
02:43:43,442 --> 02:43:44,882
the torrent is lookin’.”

2920
02:43:44,882 --> 02:43:49,103
He held out to his pony a slice of bread
matted with sardines,

2921
02:43:49,103 --> 02:43:51,380
which the pony expertly accepted.

2922
02:43:51,380 --> 02:43:55,328
“You’re a plumb pie-biter
you Monte,” he continued.

2923
02:43:55,328 --> 02:43:59,189
Monte rubbed his nose
on his master’s shoulder.

2924
02:43:59,189 --> 02:44:02,034
“I wouldn’t trust you
with berries and cream.

2925
02:44:02,034 --> -1:59:59,000
No, seh; not though yu’ did
rescue a drownin’ lady.

2926
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2927
02:44:07,564 --> 02:44:13,018
Presently he tightened the forward cinch,
got in the saddle, and the pony fell

2928
02:44:13,018 --> 02:44:16,740
into his wise mechanical jog;
for he had come a long way,

2929
02:44:16,740 --> 02:44:20,276
and was going a long way,
and he knew this as well as the man did.

2930
02:44:20,276 --> 02:44:26,071
To use the language of Cattle Land,
steers had “jumped to seventy-five.”

2931
02:44:26,071 --> 02:44:28,789
This was a great and prosperous
leap in their value.

2932
02:44:28,789 --> 02:44:33,440
To have flourished in that golden time
you need not be dead now,

2933
02:44:33,440 --> 02:44:37,814
nor even middle-aged;
but it is Wyoming mythology already⁠—

2934
02:44:37,814 --> 02:44:40,222
quite as fabulous as the high-jumping
cow.

2935
02:44:40,222 --> 02:44:46,360
Indeed, people gathered together and
behaved themselves much in the same

2936
02:44:46,360 --> 02:44:49,309
pleasant and improbable way.

2937
02:44:49,309 --> 02:44:55,783
Johnson County, and Natrona,
and Converse, and others,

2938
02:44:55,783 --> 02:44:59,983
to say nothing of the Cheyenne Club,
had been jumping over the moon for some

2939
02:44:59,983 --> 02:45:05,646
weeks, all on account of steers;
and on the strength of this vigorous

2940
02:45:05,646 --> 02:45:10,020
price of seventy-five,
the Stanton Brothers were giving a

2941
02:45:10,020 --> 02:45:14,958
barbecue at the Goose Egg outfit,
their ranch on Bear Creek.

2942
02:45:14,958 --> 02:45:18,811
Of course the whole neighborhood was
bidden, and would come forty miles to a

2943
02:45:18,811 --> 02:45:21,711
man; some would come further⁠—the
Virginian was coming

2944
02:45:21,711 --> 02:45:22,831
a hundred and eighteen.

2945
02:45:22,831 --> 02:45:26,911
It had struck him⁠—rather suddenly,
as shall be made plain⁠—that he should

2946
02:45:26,911 --> 02:45:30,659
like to see how they were getting along
up there on Bear Creek.

